   "id": "003",
   "source": {
    "title": "DHT-SWNet: Frequency-aware ship and wake detection in multi-source optical remote sensing imagery",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.03.012",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.03.012",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "This study addresses automatic detection of ship wakes in optical remote-sensing images, aiming to improve accuracy and efficiency via joint detection of ships and Kelvin wakes. First, we construct a new Remote Sensing Ship Wake (RSSW) dataset from multi-source optical imagery and develop dedicated labeling software to ensure reliable data preparation. Second, we propose the Discrete Hartley Transform Ship Wake Network (DHT-SWNet), which integrates DHT-based frequency analysis to capture the characteristic patterns of Kelvin wake. To further enhance representation, the network adopts efficient multi-scale feature integration, strengthening learning across different spatial scales. Experimental results show that the method achieves 75.63% mAP for wake detection, outperforming representative deep-learning baselines. The system simultaneously localizes ships and wakes on wide-area optical images, providing an effective tool for maritime surveillance, environmental protection, and ship navigation, and supporting subsequent ocean monitoring and analysis."
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops a wake-based vessel detection capability built around a black-box DHT-SWNet detector trained on the RSSW dataset, an optical remote sensing collection of ship wakes. The method's core technical contribution—identifying vessels from wake morphology alone—touches ethics at several points. Most directly, the paper acknowledges that the RSSW dataset may be skewed toward calm sea states and high-contrast conditions where wakes are most visible, and it candidly documents that the detector produces false positives from wake-like linear patterns such as sea clutter, cloud or haze boundaries, and land–sea edge structures. The paper also frames wake-only detection as a means of locating \"dark targets\" (vessels with AIS disabled or unregistered) and discusses generative cloud-removal reconstruction as a complementary technique, both of which carry their own ethical associations.\n\nIn terms of causal risk reasoning, two findings are actually instantiated by this paper's own method, and both are stated with moderate confidence. First, the calm-sea, high-contrast bias of the RSSW dataset promotes a geographic representation bias, conditional on data being sparse in rough-sea or low-visibility regions; this is plausibly grounded in the paper's own admission that wakes under rough or low-visibility conditions may be underrepresented. The downstream impact—unequal quality of detection across geographic regions and scales—is a strongly reasoned but only *potential* consequence, since the paper does not itself demonstrate that inequitable outcome. Second, the black-box detector's documented false-positive behavior promotes inadvertent inferential error, conditional on wake-like clutter being processed without transparent guardrails; again this is plausible but qualified rather than asserted as certain harm. By contrast, the chain from wake-only dark-target detection to inference of personal characteristics from proximity, and onward to privacy violation, is a category-level disclosure only: this method belongs to a class that can raise such privacy concerns under the stated conditions (where individuals lack control over data disclosure of those nearby), but the paper does not perform that triggering inferential step, so it cannot be raised as a finding against this work. Likewise, the path from inferential error to inequitable social outcomes remains a potential, condition-bound disclosure tied to the absence of ethical checks, not something this paper instantiates.\n\nOn mitigations, the paper neutralizes one associated risk: although diffusion-based cloud-removal reconstruction can in general introduce artificial structures that mislead wake detection, this risk is marked not triggered here, and the paper notes the concern and the need to properly constrain or verify such generative outputs rather than leaving it unaddressed. Overall, the auditor finds that of the seven validated triples, only two risks are actually instantiated by this paper's contribution—the dataset's geographic representation bias and the detector's inferential-error risk—both at moderate confidence and therefore reported as plausible, qualified findings rather than firmly established harms. The remaining four risks, including the more serious privacy and equal-rights chains, are at most disclosures of category-level risk that this paper does not trigger, and one further risk is already neutralized by the paper's own caveats. The instantiated findings are real but modestly grounded; the privacy narrative, in particular, should not be charged against this paper.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (wake-only dark-target vessel detection:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inference of personal characteristics from proximity:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When wake morphology is used to identify vessels sailing with AIS disabled or unregistered)\n- (inference of personal characteristics from proximity:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When an individual has no control over the data disclosure of those in close proximity)\n- (calm-sea high-visibility dataset bias (RSSW):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When data is sparse in rough-sea / low-visibility regions or privileges high-contrast conditions)\n- (geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (unequal quality of geoparsing services across geographic regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Across global and local scales)\n- (black-box DHT-SWNet detector with false-positive risk:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When wake-like linear patterns and clutter are processed without transparent guardrails)\n- (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable social outcomes:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the absence of ethical guides to provide checks and balances on data and methods)\n- (diffusion-based cloud removal reconstruction:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When generative reconstruction introduces artificial structures into imagery)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: wake-only dark-target vessel detection, calm-sea high-visibility dataset bias (RSSW), black-box DHT-SWNet detector with false-positive risk, diffusion-based cloud removal reconstruction\n  RiskMechanism: inference of personal characteristics from proximity, geographic representation bias, inadvertent inferential error\n  EthicalImpact: privacy violation, unequal quality of geoparsing services across geographic regions, inequitable social outcomes",
