   "id": "009",
   "source": {
    "title": "Towards assessing the synthetic-to-measured adversarial vulnerability of SAR ATR",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2024.06.004",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2024.06.004",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2024",
    "abstract": "Recently, there has been increasing concern about the vulnerability of deep neural network (DNN)-based synthetic aperture radar (SAR) automatic target recognition (ATR) to adversarial attacks, where a DNN could be easily deceived by clean input with imperceptible but aggressive perturbations. This paper studies the synthetic-to-measured (S2M) transfer setting, where an attacker generates adversarial perturbation based solely on synthetic data and transfers it against victim models trained with measured data. Compared with the current measured-to-measured (M2M) transfer setting, our approach does not need direct access to the victim model or the measured SAR data. We also propose the transferability estimation attack (TEA) to uncover the adversarial risks in this more challenging and practical scenario. The TEA makes full use of the limited similarity between the synthetic and measured data pairs for blind estimation and optimization of S2M transferability, leading to feasible surrogate model enhancement without mastering the victim model and data. Comprehensive evaluations based on the publicly available synthetic and measured paired labeled experiment (SAMPLE) dataset demonstrate that the TEA outperforms state-of-the-art methods and can significantly enhance various attack algorithms in computer vision and remote sensing applications. Codes and data are available at https://github.com/scenarri/S2M-TEA."
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper investigates the vulnerability of deep neural network–based synthetic aperture radar (SAR) automatic target recognition (ATR) to adversarial attacks, focusing specifically on the synthetic-to-measured (S2M) transfer setting in which an attacker generates adversarial perturbations based solely on synthetic data and transfers them against victim models trained with measured data. Its central technical contribution is the proposed transferability estimation attack (TEA), evaluated on the publicly available SAMPLE dataset. The paper touches ethics directly because its method is an offensive adversarial technique: it constructs imperceptible but aggressive perturbations and explicitly aims to \"uncover the adversarial risks\" in this challenging and practical threat scenario. These are the trigger points at which the work's own method engages with risk mechanisms rather than merely discussing them in the abstract.\n\nTwo findings are actually instantiated by this paper's contribution, and both are strongly grounded. First, the auditor finds that the paper's use of adversarial perturbations promotes the misleading of machine learning models into yielding incorrect predictions, conditional on the inference stage of SAR ATR under the S2M transfer setting; this is directly evidenced by the paper's own proposal of the TEA to expose adversarial risk in this scenario. Second, the auditor finds that these adversarial perturbations promote the prediction of incorrect results in high-risk geoscience and remote sensing applications, conditioned on the realistic S2M threat against SAR ATR, as demonstrated by the paper's reported ability to outperform state-of-the-art methods and enhance existing attack algorithms. Both findings are conditional on the S2M / SAR ATR setting and should be read as such rather than as absolute claims. Beyond these, two further triples are only POTENTIAL disclosures, not findings against this paper: the chain by which incorrect predictions could promote safety risks in critical missions (such as military and maritime surveillance), and the chain by which incorrect results in high-risk applications could promote threats to human safety in emergency situations (such as disaster response, surveillance, and reconnaissance). These downstream physical-harm impacts belong to the category of safety-critical deployments that SAR ATR can serve, but the paper itself does not instantiate any such deployment or operational mission, so they are reported here strictly as category-level risk disclosures and not as harms the paper realizes.\n\nNo mitigation triples are present in the validated set; while the surrounding domain context discusses adversarial defenses such as adversarial training, no such defense is attributed to this paper within the validated triples, so the auditor records no instantiated mitigation. In overall judgement, two of the four validated risks are actually instantiated by this paper's contribution and two are merely disclosed at the category level, with no risks already neutralized. The two instantiated findings are both strongly grounded in the paper's own text and method, so the auditor states them as genuine findings—the paper advances an attack that, in the SAR ATR S2M setting, demonstrably misleads models and produces incorrect predictions in a high-risk application domain. The escalation from those technical errors to physical or human-safety harm, however, remains a potential consequence tied to deployment conditions the paper does not itself enter, and the audit treats it accordingly as disclosure rather than realized impact.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (adversarial perturbations:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: inference stage of machine learning models in SAR ATR under the S2M transfer setting)\n- (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: safety-critical geoscience and remote sensing tasks such as SAR ATR for military and maritime surveillance)\n- (adversarial perturbations:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: In the context of automated driving or critical image classification, here SAR ATR under realistic S2M threat)\n- (prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (threats to human safety in emergency situations:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When applied to safety-critical missions like disaster response, surveillance, and reconnaissance)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: adversarial perturbations\n  RiskMechanism: misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions, prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions, threats to human safety in emergency situations",
