   "id": "010",
   "source": {
    "title": "Improving interpretability of deep active learning for flood inundation mapping through class ambiguity indices using multi-spectral satellite imagery",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2024.114213",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2024.114213",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2024",
    "abstract": "Flood inundation mapping is a critical task for responding to the increasing risk of flooding linked to global warming. Significant advancements of deep learning in recent years have triggered its extensive applications, including flood inundation mapping. To cope with the time-consuming and labor-intensive data labeling process in supervised learning, deep active learning strategies are one of the feasible approaches. However, there remains limited exploration into the interpretability of how deep active learning strategies operate, with a specific focus on flood inundation mapping in the field of remote sensing. In this study, we introduce a novel framework of Interpretable Deep Active Learning for Flood inundation Mapping (IDAL-FIM), specifically in terms of class ambiguity of multi-spectral satellite images. In the experiments, we utilize Sen1Floods11 dataset, and adopt U-Net with MC-dropout. In addition, we employ five acquisition functions, which are the random, K-means, BALD, entropy, and margin acquisition functions. Based on the experimental results, we demonstrate that two proposed class ambiguity indices are effective variables to interpret the deep active learning by establishing statistically significant correlation with the predictive uncertainty of the deep learning model at the tile level. Then, we illustrate the behaviors of deep active learning through visualizing two-dimensional density plots and providing interpretations regarding the operation of deep act"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit: Interpretable Deep Active Learning for Flood Inundation Mapping (IDAL-FIM)**\n\nThis paper develops a deep active learning framework for flood inundation mapping from multi-spectral satellite imagery, employing a U-Net architecture with MC-dropout for segmentation and uncertainty estimation, and validated on the Sen1Floods11 dataset. The work touches on ethics at two principal points. First, it operates within a class of methods—deep active learning—whose predictive process the authors themselves describe as opaque, owing to the black-box nature of deep neural networks. This is the paper's most direct ethical trigger: the auditor finds that the method instantiates a genuine concern regarding the lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, conditioned on the opacity and limited interpretability of the deep active learning process. Second, the application domain itself—flood emergency response—is a safety-critical, high-risk setting, which raises the question of whether opaque predictions could propagate into operational consequences.\n\nTurning to the causal risk reasoning, the auditor distinguishes findings actually instantiated by this paper from category-level risks merely disclosed. As an instantiated finding, the paper's reliance on black-box deep learning promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency; this is a strongly grounded observation, stated by the authors in their own framing of the problem. However, the downstream impact—safety risks in critical missions such as flood emergency response—is tagged POTENTIAL rather than instantiated: this paper belongs to a class of high-risk remote-sensing applications where opaque predictions could in principle threaten safety, but the paper does not itself demonstrate or perform an action that realizes such physical harm, so it is reported here only as a conditional category disclosure, not as a finding against the paper. Similarly, the risk that unrepresentative geographic training data could promote resource allocation inequality is a POTENTIAL disclosure: the authors note that a non-uniform unlabeled data pool may compromise the effectiveness of the density-based acquisition function, but the paper does not instantiate a scenario in which models perform well only in regions present in the pool while target regions differ. This equity concern therefore remains a conditional, category-level risk rather than an actual harm caused by the contribution.\n\nOn mitigations, the auditor finds the paper substantively responsive to the very risk it most directly triggers. The IDAL-FIM framework introduces operable interpretability mechanisms—the proposed class ambiguity indices (BPR and MDF)—which are shown to correlate statistically with the model's predictive uncertainty at the tile level, thereby inhibiting the lack of transparency under the stated condition that these indices address the real-world consequences of opaque selection. Additionally, the adoption of MC-dropout uncertainty quantification inhibits the unreliability of predictions in safety-critical tasks within high-risk remote-sensing applications. In overall judgement, of the five validated triples, three are instantiated—one risk and two mitigations—and two are potential disclosures, with none neutralized as not-triggered. The single instantiated risk (opacity of the deep learning process) is strongly grounded in the paper's own text, but it is directly and strongly paired with instantiated mitigations that the paper explicitly contributes. The auditor's assessment is therefore that this paper not only discloses but actively addresses its principal instantiated risk, while the safety and equity impacts remain conditional, category-level disclosures the paper does not itself realize.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: deep active learning process is opaque and interpretability is limited)\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications such as flood emergency response)\n- (operable ai ethics guidelines:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: interpretability mechanisms (BPR and MDF indices) address specific real-world consequences of opaque selection)\n- (uncertainty quantification:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications using MC-dropout uncertainty estimation)\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: when models perform well only in regions present in the unlabeled pool while target regions differ)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks, unrepresentative geographic training data\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions, resource allocation inequality\n  Mitigation: operable ai ethics guidelines, uncertainty quantification",
