   "id": "011",
   "source": {
    "title": "Social sensing from street-level imagery: A case study in learning spatio-temporal urban mobility patterns",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2019.04.017",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2019.04.017",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2019",
    "abstract": "Street-level imagery has covered the comprehensive landscape of urban areas. Compared to satellite imagery, this new source of image data has the advantage in fine-grained observations of not only physical environment but also social sensing. Prior studies using street-level imagery focus primarily on urban physical environment auditing. In this study, we demonstrate the potential usage of street-level imagery in uncovering spatio-temporal urban mobility patterns. Our method assumes that the streetscape depicted in street-level imagery reflects urban functions and that urban streets of similar functions exhibit similar temporal mobility patterns. We present how a deep convolutional neural network (DCNN) can be trained to identify high-level scene features from street view images that can explain up to 66.5% of the hourly variation of taxi trips along with the urban road network. The study shows that street-level imagery, as the counterpart of remote sensing imagery, provides an opportunity to infer fine-scale human activity information of an urban region and bridge gaps between the physical space and human space. This approach can therefore facilitate urban environment observation and smart urban planning."
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops a deep learning approach that infers fine-scale human mobility from street-level imagery, treating the street as the basic spatial aggregation unit and using taxi pick-up and drop-off \"diurnal signatures\" as a proxy for urban mobility. The method touches ethics at several points. By inferring fine-scale human activity from imagery, it belongs to a class of techniques capable of disclosing sensitive geospatial information such as home locations, workspaces, and daily trajectories. By aggregating data to the street level, it raises questions of geographic representation, and by relying on taxi-trip data it embeds assumptions about which segments of the urban population are observed. The authors themselves acknowledge that bias exists in approximating urban mobility from taxi pick-ups and drop-offs, and that the modifiable areal unit problem (MAUP) affects how values are computed for short streets.\n\nSeparating actual findings from category-level disclosures, the auditor identifies two risks that this paper genuinely instantiates. First, the choice to treat each street as an individual spatial unit promotes geographic representation bias; this is a moderately supported finding, evidenced directly by the paper's own description of over-estimation for the short \"Side Road of South 3rd Ring\" due to MAUP. Second, training the model on taxi-trip data that represents only formal taxi users promotes population bias, again a moderately supported finding, since the authors concede that taxi-based proxies do not fully capture actual urban mobility; this risk holds under the condition that the dataset fails to represent the actual target population. The remaining five triples are disclosures only, not findings against this paper. The inference of fine-scale mobility from imagery belongs to a class that can promote disclosure of sensitive geospatial data and thereby a location privacy violation—but only conditionally, when home locations, workspaces, and trajectories are exposed—and this paper does not instantiate that exposure. Likewise, geographic representation bias can in principle lead to systematic exclusion of smaller communities, and population bias can promote resource allocation inequality in land-use and traffic-planning contexts, while geographic heterogeneity limiting transferability can promote resource allocation inequality when models work only in data-rich areas; each of these downstream equal-rights impacts is associated with the technique class but is not triggered by the paper's own contribution.\n\nIn terms of mitigations, the paper's principal strength is transparency: it openly discusses the bias inherent in its taxi-trip proxy and explicitly diagnoses the MAUP effect on short street units, which constitutes a form of self-disclosure rather than concealment. No further technical safeguards against privacy disclosure or representation bias are present in the validated triples. Overall, the auditor's judgement is that of the seven validated risk relationships, only two are actually instantiated by this paper—geographic representation bias from street-level aggregation and population bias from taxi-only training data—both at moderate confidence and both qualified by their stated conditions rather than asserted as certain harms. The five remaining relationships, including the more serious privacy-violation and resource-allocation-inequality pathways, are category-level disclosures that this paper does not trigger and should not be read as findings against it. The instantiated findings are reasonably well-grounded in the paper's own acknowledged limitations, but the paper does not itself perform the privacy-exposing actions that would elevate the disclosure-level risks into audit findings.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (deep learning model inferring fine-scale human mobility from street-level imagery:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When exposing home locations, workspaces, and daily trajectories)\n- (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (location privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When exposing home locations, workspaces, and daily trajectories)\n- (treating each street as the spatial aggregation unit:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>\n- (geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systematic exclusion of smaller communities from accurate geographic representation:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>\n- (model trained on taxi-trip data representing only formal taxi users:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When datasets fail to represent actual target regions)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n- (geographic heterogeneity limiting transferability of streetscape-mobility relationship:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: when models perform well only in data-rich urban areas)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: deep learning model inferring fine-scale human mobility from street-level imagery, treating each street as the spatial aggregation unit, model trained on taxi-trip data representing only formal taxi users, geographic heterogeneity limiting transferability of streetscape-mobility relationship\n  RiskMechanism: disclosure of sensitive geospatial data, geographic representation bias, population bias\n  EthicalImpact: location privacy violation, systematic exclusion of smaller communities from accurate geographic representation, resource allocation inequality",
