   "id": "012",
   "source": {
    "title": "Universal adversarial defense in remote sensing based on pre-trained denoising diffusion models",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2024.104131",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2024.104131",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2024",
    "abstract": "Deep neural networks (DNNs) have risen to prominence as key solutions in numerous AI applications for earth observation (AI4EO). However, their susceptibility to adversarial examples poses a critical challenge, compromising the reliability of AI4EO algorithms. This paper presents a novel Universal Adversarial Defense approach in Remote Sensing Imagery (UAD-RS), leveraging pre-trained diffusion models to protect DNNs against various adversarial examples exhibiting heterogeneous adversarial patterns. Specifically, a universal adversarial purification framework is developed utilizing pre-trained diffusion models to mitigate adversarial perturbations through the introduction of Gaussian noise and subsequent purification of the perturbations from adversarial examples. Additionally, an Adaptive Noise Level Selection (ANLS) mechanism is introduced to determine the optimal noise level for the purification framework with a task-guided Fréchet Inception Distance (FID) ranking strategy, thereby enhancing purification performance. Consequently, only a single pre-trained diffusion model is required for purifying various adversarial examples with heterogeneous adversarial patterns across each dataset, significantly reducing training efforts for multiple attack settings while maintaining high performance without prior knowledge of adversarial perturbations. Experimental results on four heterogeneous RS datasets, focusing on scene classification and semantic segmentation, demonstrate that UA"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper presents UAD-RS (Universal Adversarial Defense in Remote Sensing Imagery), a universal adversarial purification framework that leverages pre-trained denoising diffusion probabilistic models (DDPMs) to protect deep neural networks against adversarial examples in AI for Earth Observation (AI4EO) settings. Mechanically, the framework eliminates adversarial perturbations by first forward-diffusing the input with Gaussian noise and then reverse-denoising it, thereby disrupting heterogeneous adversarial patterns without requiring a separate training session for each attack type. The ethical surface this work touches is the well-documented vulnerability of remote sensing deep learning models to adversarial perturbations—imperceptible modifications that can fool state-of-the-art models into producing high-confidence incorrect predictions—which is particularly consequential in safety-critical geoscience and remote sensing tasks.\n\nIn terms of causal risk reasoning, this paper's actual contribution is protective rather than harmful, so its single instantiated finding is a positive one: the auditor finds, with moderate confidence, that the UAD-RS purification framework inhibits the risk mechanism whereby adversarial perturbations mislead machine learning models into incorrect predictions, conditional on adversarial perturbations being present in high-risk AI4EO applications. This is reported as a qualified, plausible finding rather than an asserted certainty, given the moderate (inferred) grounding. The remaining risk-bearing triples are category-level disclosures that this paper does not instantiate. The broader chain by which incorrect predictions in high-risk geoscience tasks could promote threats to human safety in emergency situations, and by which misled models could promote safety risks in critical missions—both tagged with potential physical harm and conditioned on safety-critical settings such as disaster response—belong to the general AI4EO threat landscape this work seeks to mitigate, not to actions this paper performs. Likewise, the mechanism by which adversarial perturbations at inference mislead models is marked as not triggered, since the paper's method works to neutralize precisely this mechanism through its noise-disruption-and-denoising process.\n\nThe mitigation in this case is the paper's own central contribution: the diffusion-based purification framework directly inhibits the adversarial-perturbation risk mechanism it targets. Weighing the evidence, the auditor finds that of the five validated triples, only one is actually instantiated by this paper, and that instantiation is defensive rather than a harm—the paper attenuates a recognized risk rather than creating one. Three further triples are merely disclosures of category-level risks that this work does not trigger, and one risk mechanism is explicitly neutralized by the method's design. The single instantiated finding rests on moderate, inferred grounding, so it should be read as plausible and qualified rather than firmly established from verbatim text. Overall, the auditor identifies no ethical risk that is actually instantiated as a harm by this paper's contribution; the remaining items are disclosures of the broader AI4EO security context that motivates, but is not introduced by, this defensive work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (universal adversarial purification framework (UAD-RS) using pre-trained diffusion models:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When adversarial perturbations mislead deep learning models in high-risk AI4EO applications)\n- (universal adversarial purification framework (UAD-RS) using pre-trained diffusion models:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In safety-critical geoscience and remote sensing tasks such as disaster response)\n- (prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (threats to human safety in emergency situations:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When applied to safety-critical missions like disaster response)\n- (adversarial perturbations:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>  (when: inference stage of machine learning models)\n- (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: safety-critical geoscience and remote sensing tasks)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: adversarial perturbations\n  RiskMechanism: misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions, prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications\n  EthicalImpact: threats to human safety in emergency situations, safety risks in critical missions\n  Mitigation: universal adversarial purification framework (UAD-RS) using pre-trained diffusion models",
