   "id": "017",
   "source": {
    "title": "Causal Graph Neural Networks for robust wildfire forecasting across geographic shifts",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.03.018",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.03.018",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Machine learning has become a powerful tool for modeling the relationships between environmental factors and fire events. However, beyond the predictive performance, we argue that critical decision-making requires an understanding of fire mechanisms to improve reliability. Causality offers a promising framework for explicitly analyzing the interdependencies among factors; however, its integration into deep learning and further application in disaster management remain largely underexplored. To map the relationship between historical inputs and resulting burned areas, we proposed a causally informed deep learning approach using graph models. The graph representation is constructed through a learnable approach supervised by causal knowledge. A graph pooling layer, informed by backdoor adjustment criteria, mitigates the potential confounding effects of hidden variables on the target variable. Our experiments demonstrate that our model is more robust, reducing the AUROC standard deviation at longer forecasting horizons by 64% and improving performance under geographical distribution shifts by 2 points compared to the baseline. Compared with fully connected and correlation-based graphs, the causally informed graph proved to be more resilient to input perturbations. Additionally, our model revealed the lagged effect of Oceanic Climate Index variables on local fire events and the critical role of short-term local precipitation—indicating that Mediterranean fires are mostly drought-d"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops a spatio-temporal predictive model for wildfire prediction built around graph-based deep learning, and its methodological choices touch on several ethics-relevant axes. The model is, by category, a deep learning system for wildfire prediction—a class of model that is widely regarded as among the least interpretable—so the question of algorithmic transparency arises naturally. The paper also makes a deliberate cross-region design choice: it trains on Middle East fire data (with a higher burned-area fraction of 1.029%) and tests on more challenging European scenarios (0.857%), which engages the question of representation bias across distinct fire management regions. Finally, the paper explicitly situates its work within the demands of operational wildfire management, where downstream uses such as early warning and evacuation decisions carry real-world stakes.\n\nTurning to the causal risk reasoning, it is important to separate what this paper actually triggers from what its technique class merely implies. The one finding genuinely instantiated by this paper is, in fact, a mitigation rather than a harm: the paper employs causally informed graph pooling with backdoor adjustment, conditioning on geographic context to avoid spurious region-specific correlations and to capture true causal fire drivers, which works to inhibit the lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability. Stated with moderate confidence, this is a constructive design choice that the auditor reads as the paper actively addressing interpretability rather than aggravating it; correspondingly, the black-box transparency risk that deep learning models would otherwise promote is recorded here as not triggered, because the paper's own architecture is oriented against it. The remaining risks are disclosures of category-level concern that this paper does not instantiate. The transfer of a predictive model across distinct fire management regions belongs to a class that can introduce neighborhood representation bias when a model trained on one region (Middle East) is applied to another (Europe) with differing burn rates and policy contexts—but this is reported as a potential category risk, not a finding against the paper. That representation bias, in turn, is strongly associated in general with downstream inequitable outcomes—specifically, conditional on smaller fires or scattered burn patterns in under-represented areas being systematically missed, biasing resource-allocation outcomes—yet again this is a disclosure of where the chain *could* lead, not something the paper is shown to enact. Likewise, the strong link from a lack of transparency to safety risks in critical missions holds only conditionally, for high-risk applications such as operational wildfire early warning and evacuation, and is flagged as potential rather than realized.\n\nOn mitigations, the paper's most salient measure is the backdoor-adjustment graph pooling layer described above, which directly targets confounding and transparency, and the paper further acknowledges that operational deployment would require dedicated pipelines for model verification, human-in-the-loop validation, and continuous retraining under non-stationary conditions—an explicit recognition of the safety conditions surrounding critical use. In the auditor's overall judgement, of the five validated triples only one is actually instantiated by this paper, and that one is a mitigation; three are potential, category-level disclosures that the paper does not trigger, and one transparency risk is affirmatively not triggered. Accordingly, the auditor finds no ethical harm actually instantiated by this paper's contribution. The representation-bias and safety-risk concerns, though some are strongly grounded as general causal mechanisms, remain disclosures of risks inherent to cross-region transfer and operational deployment that this paper does not itself realize, and they should be read as cautions for any future operational use rather than as findings against the present work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box deep learning model for wildfire prediction:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | n/a>  (when: When deep learning models are widely considered the least interpretable, hindering trust in critical fire management decisions)\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications such as operational wildfire early warning and evacuation decisions)\n- (causally informed graph pooling with backdoor adjustment:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When the model conditions on geographic context to avoid learning spurious region-specific correlations and to capture true causal fire drivers)\n- (spatio-temporal predictive model transferred across distinct fire management regions:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (neighborhood representation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When a model trained on one region (Middle East) is applied to another (Europe) with different burn rates and policy contexts, introducing representation bias)\n- (neighborhood representation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (biased law enforcement outcomes:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Neighborhood level, when smaller fires or scattered burn patterns in under-represented areas are systematically missed, biasing resource allocation outcomes)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box deep learning model for wildfire prediction, spatio-temporal predictive model transferred across distinct fire management regions\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, neighborhood representation bias\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions, biased law enforcement outcomes\n  Mitigation: causally informed graph pooling with backdoor adjustment",
