   "id": "021",
   "source": {
    "title": "DVGBench: Implicit-to-explicit visual grounding benchmark in UAV imagery with large vision–language models",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.01.005",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.01.005",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Remote sensing (RS) large vision–language models (LVLMs) have shown strong promise across visual grounding (VG) tasks. However, existing RS VG datasets predominantly rely on explicit referring expressions – such as relative position, relative size, and color cues – thereby constraining performance on implicit VG tasks that require scenario-specific domain knowledge. This article introduces DVGBench, a high-quality implicit VG benchmark for drones, covering six major application scenarios: traffic, disaster, security, sport, social activity, and productive activity. Each object provides both explicit and implicit queries. Based on the dataset, we design DroneVG-R1, an LVLM that integrates the novel Implicit-to-Explicit Chain-of-Thought (I2E-CoT) within a reinforcement learning paradigm. This enables the model to take advantage of scene-specific expertise, converting implicit references into explicit ones and thus reducing grounding difficulty. Finally, an evaluation of mainstream models on both explicit and implicit VG tasks reveals substantial limitations in their reasoning capabilities. These findings provide actionable insights for advancing the reasoning capacity of LVLMs for drone-based agents. The code and datasets will be released at https://github.com/zytx121/DVGBench."
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops and evaluates models for parsing referring expressions over high-resolution UAV (drone) imagery across a range of operational scenarios, including disaster response, security, and social-activity monitoring. The ethically salient trigger lies in the resolution of the imagery and the explicit downstream uses to which it is put: the paper's own examples describe identifying individuals awaiting rescue, recognizing illegal vehicles, police and patrol cars, demonstrators and police officers, locating fugitives by tracking searchlights at night, and identifying designated individuals to ensure event safety. These are not abstract capabilities but tasks the paper instantiates, and they are precisely the conditions under which fine-grained aerial imagery becomes capable of discerning and tracking individuals. The paper also touches ethics at the evaluation layer, where it confronts a realistic data collection bias arising from the uneven distribution of question types and scenarios in its benchmark.\n\nOn the causal reasoning, the auditor finds that high-resolution UAV imagery promotes unintentional disclosure of sensitive information under the stated condition that resolution is fine enough to discern individuals; because the paper's stated security and social-activity applications—locating fugitives, identifying designated individuals—meet that condition, this is reported as an actual, strongly grounded audit finding rather than a hypothetical. Following from this, the disclosure mechanism in turn promotes a location, behavior, and association privacy violation; this is an instantiated finding as well, though presented with moderate qualification, plausibly supported by the paper's own description of tracking pursued fugitives and identifying designated persons. By contrast, the chain leading from evaluation bias to reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions is only a POTENTIAL, category-level disclosure: the concern that aggregate metrics can mask regional or scenario variability and degrade fairness in deployment belongs to the class of risks this technique can raise, and the paper acknowledges that its models still struggle with very small-area-ratio objects, but the paper does not itself instantiate that fairness harm—indeed it actively works against it.\n\nIn terms of mitigations, the paper does not leave the evaluation-bias risk unaddressed: it adopts a category-averaging method when computing overall accuracy precisely to ensure a fair evaluation and to expose where the model is biased across scenarios, and this spatially-explicit, category-averaged evaluation is a strongly grounded mitigation that inhibits the evaluation-bias mechanism. Accordingly, the related non-spatially-explicit aggregate-scoring risk is treated as NOT_TRIGGERED, noted here only to record that the paper neutralizes rather than incurs it. Overall, the auditor's judgement is that two distinct risks are genuinely instantiated by this paper's contribution—the privacy-relevant disclosure from high-resolution UAV imagery (strongly grounded) and the resulting location/behavior/association privacy violation (instantiated but moderately qualified)—both stemming from the same surveillance-oriented application set. The evaluation-fairness concern is a disclosure only, and the corresponding aggregate-metric risk is actively mitigated. The instantiated privacy findings are well-grounded in the paper's own stated use cases and should be taken seriously, while the privacy harms remain conditional on imagery resolution sufficient to identify individuals, which the paper's described applications appear to satisfy.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (high-resolution uav imagery:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (unintentional disclosure of sensitive information:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When resolution is fine enough to discern individuals in drone imagery used for security, disaster and social activity scenarios)\n- (unintentional disclosure of sensitive information:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (location behavior and association privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus with uneven scenario distribution)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of geoparsers for downstream geospatial tasks)\n- (spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: By using category-averaging to expose where a model is biased across scenarios)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: high-resolution uav imagery, non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score\n  RiskMechanism: unintentional disclosure of sensitive information, evaluation bias hiding regional variability\n  EthicalImpact: location behavior and association privacy violation, reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions\n  Mitigation: spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection",
