     "content": "text data analytics in geography. Behl et al. (2021) used the  XAI method LIME to investigate misclassification of tweets from two earthquakes, Italy and Nepal, attempting  to identify which words nudged tweets toward usefulness (or not). Zhou et al. (2022) employed Graph Neural  Networks with Volunteered Geographic Information to refine geolocations of tweets. They combined LIME and  another XAI method, LRP, to explain the geolocation inference behavior of DNN. While promising, geographic  structures like geometry and topology can still be limited. Zhou et al.'s (2022) paper only used distance, or the  hop in LRP. Remote sensing imagery data analysis, because of its relation to computer vision, is another domain to which  XAI is applied. Abdollahi and Pradhan  (2021) chose the commonly used XAI method SHAP to explain vegetation  classification results from probably the most popular, DNN, a convolutional neural network (CNN). (SHAP will be  further defined in Section 3.) Their research was performance-  based: gain insights for hyperparameter tuning  and training data selection as a way to improve classification accuracy. Guo et al.  (2021) sought to reduce training  and testing time (“neuron and layer pruning”) of CNNs by relying on XAI algorithms in their land use classification  studies. Like above, the authors focused on classification optimization rather than, for example, consider the role  of the surrounding geospatial neighborhood in explaining the results of the pruning. SHAP and LIME are popular in GeoAI studies, whether DNNs or not. Yang et al. (2021) employed spatially  explicit predictive modeling called XGBoost with SHAP to investigate truck crashes; the XAI showed a strong  correlation of crashes to the density of road usage and the adjacency to seaports. Li  (2022) compared XGBoost to  a geographically weighted regression to predict the geographic distribution of ride-  hailing service demand. Li used  SHAP to examine combinations of input variables"
