     "content": "by the  formula (1). y = X 1 × β (u, v)+error  (1) where y represents the dependent variable, X1 denotes the  independent variable, β (u, v) represents the parameter to  be fitted. The experimental area is defined as a 100 × 100  spatial grid and u and v represent the spatial coordinates.  The variable ˆβ (u, v) is the fitted result for this parameter  from the GWR model after post-optimization processing. A spatial continuity test was then conducted on ˆβ (u, v),  as shown in Fig. 6. The visualization of the parameter’s spa- tial distribution reveals regions where discontinuities occur,  and the red boxes highlight the resulting errors. Further - more, Fig. 6 also includes visualizations of the gradient  magnitude of ˆβ (u, v) and the correctness of this coef - ficient estimate. These combined results demonstrate that  areas with spatial discontinuities in the ˆβ (u, v) estimates,  particularly where the gradient magnitude is high, tend to  exhibit a high concentration of errors. In other words, errors  in the GWR fitting process cluster in these regions of abrupt  parameter change. The real-world dataset comprises Cook County census tract– level demographic records, including total population and  racial composition (“White”, “Black”, “Asian”, and “Other  Race”), used to visualize population heterogeneity and spatial  distribution patterns. A spatial analysis that treats Cook County  as a single, uniform entity would produce an “average” demo- graphic profile that represents no actual community, thereby  obscuring the distinct realities of its diverse populations. The PCP in Fig. 5 (a) serves as an essential first step in  this process. By plotting each census tract as an individual  line across multiple racial composition dimensions, the PCP  immediately dismantles any assumption of homogeneity.  The PCP visualization illustrates the distribution patterns of  each census tract across different racial population counts. These patterns are not limited to the level"
