   "source": {
    "title": "A survey on vision-based outdoor smoke detection techniques for environmental safety",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2022.01.013",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2022.01.013",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2022",
    "abstract": "Early stage smoke detection using image and video analysis is an important area of research due to its enormous applications in mitigating fire hazards and ensuring environmental safety. Numerous solutions have been proposed for real-time smoke detection using conventional image processing, machine learning, and deep learning techniques. Smoke pattern, motion analysis, color and texture are important characteristics that help identify it in the outdoor environment. Vision-based Smoke detection algorithms can be broadly classified into three categories: smoke classification, segmentation, and bounding box estimation. This paper presents a comprehensive survey of existing techniques on smoke detection in the outdoor environment using image and video analysis. To perform the survey, initially 271 articles were collected from different sources like Google Scholar, Science Direct, IEEE Xplore, SpringerLink, Wiley and ACM Digital Library using the keyword search. Based on their focus on the vision-based solutions for the outdoor environment, 126 articles were identified as relevant to the present survey. Starting from the initial IP approaches that are frequently referred in the literature, machine learning and deep learning approaches have also been reviewed for each type of smoke detection. Performance of algorithms, datasets used in the research, evaluation metrics, challenges and future directions of research are also discussed."
   },
   "report": "**Audit Report**\n\nThe paper under review surveys and discusses AI-driven techniques applied to remote sensing and geoscience tasks, touching on several methodologies that intersect with recognized ethical concern areas. Specifically, it engages with AI-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data, the use of non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics such as precision, recall, and F-score, the reliance on geographic training data drawn from particular corpora, the black-box nature of deep neural networks, and the application of generative adversarial networks (GANs). Each of these technical features is a recognized point of contact with ethical risk in the GeoAI literature, and each accordingly establishes a category-level trigger that this audit must consider. The audit's task is to determine whether the paper's own contribution actually instantiates any of these risks or whether it merely belongs to a class of methods generally associated with them.\n\nOn the central question of causal risk reasoning, the auditor finds that none of the seven validated triples are instantiated by this paper's own method; all seven are classified as POTENTIAL disclosures. As such, they must be reported strictly as category-level risks that the paper does not itself trigger, not as findings against it. By disclosure, the paper belongs to a class of work where AI-driven building detection can promote misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, but only under the condition that training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types — a condition this paper is not shown to instantiate. Similarly, reliance on aggregate, non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics is associated with evaluation bias that can hide regional variability when performance is measured only as an overall corpus score, which in turn is linked to reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions during geoparser deployment; this constitutes a recognized equal-rights concern at the category level, but the paper does not perform the triggering aggregation. Likewise, unrepresentative geographic training data is associated with resource allocation inequality when models perform well only in data-rich urban areas; the black-box nature of deep neural networks is associated with a lack of algorithmic transparency that, in high-risk applications, can promote safety risks in critical missions; and GANs are associated with geospatial misinformation when models create unrealistic artifacts in map designs. In every case the condition that would convert the disclosure into an actual harm is not shown to be met by this paper, so none rise to the level of an audit finding.\n\nBecause no triple is classified as NOT_TRIGGERED, the audit identifies no mitigation that the paper actively performs to neutralize these risks; rather, the appropriate characterization is that the paper is ethics-silent or out of scope with respect to instantiating any of them. The auditor's overall judgement is therefore plain: of the seven validated triples, zero are instantiated as actual risks of this paper's contribution and all seven are merely category-level disclosures. While the underlying causal associations are themselves well-grounded (all seven carry STRONG confidence), that strength governs only how firmly the general category-level relationship is established, not whether this paper triggers it. Accordingly, the auditor raises no instantiated ethical finding against this paper and records only that its methods belong to classes of techniques carrying the conditional risks described above.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types)\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of geoparsers for downstream geospatial tasks)\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: when models perform well only in data-rich urban areas)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (generative adversarial networks gans:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (geospatial misinformation:EthicalImpact) [PsychologicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When models create unrealistic artifacts in map designs)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data, non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score, unrepresentative geographic training data, black-box nature of deep neural networks, generative adversarial networks gans\n  RiskMechanism: misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, evaluation bias hiding regional variability, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions, resource allocation inequality, safety risks in critical missions, geospatial misinformation",
