   "id": "039",
   "source": {
    "title": "Deep learning and automatic reference label harvesting for Sentinel-1 SAR-based rapid tropical dry forest disturbance mapping",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113799",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113799",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "The advent of temporally dense radar data such as the Sentinel-1 SAR have opened the door for rapid forest disturbance detection in the humid tropics. Tropical dry forest disturbance detection, however, were challenged by seasonality and more open canopy characteristics. In this manuscript, we proposed a Sentinel-1 SAR and deep learning based rapid forest disturbance detection approach for tropical dry forests. We demonstrated a weakly supervised method for reference label harvesting based on medium resolution globally available forest and forest disturbance maps. We trained a deep neural network model to derive forest and forest disturbance probabilities from Sentinel-1 images in the first step. We then implemented a probabilistic disturbance detection and refinement method to map forest disturbances in near real-time in two test regions in Paraguay and Mozambique. We mapped new forest disturbances in an emulated near real-time scenario for 2020 and 2021 and evaluated the spatial accuracy of the disturbance alerts by generating area adjusted precision, recall and F-1 score. We also evaluated the improvement in timeliness of disturbance detection by estimating mean time difference of disturbance events detection with that of Landsat-based GLAD alerts. The generated alerts in Paraguay and Mozambique achieved a precision, recall and F-1 score of 0.99, 0.61, 0.75 and 0.97, 0.51, 0.66, respectively. The proposed method detected disturbances with a mean of 21 days ( ± 18 days) ear"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops a SAR-based deep learning system for near-real-time forest disturbance detection, applied across two distinct study regions, Paraguay and Mozambique. Methodologically, it trains separate models per region and polarization to accommodate variability in tropical dry forest seasonality and forest types, and it derives its training labels through a weakly supervised approach that iteratively refines noisy forest-loss data harvested from the globally available Hansen 2020 forest-cover loss dataset. These two design choices — region-specific modelling applied across eco-regions, and weak label harvesting from coarse global maps — are the principal points where the work touches on ethics, alongside the more general fact that disturbance maps of this kind can in principle be repurposed for monitoring of logging operations or individuals.\n\nOn the causal reasoning, it is important to state clearly that no triple in this audit is instantiated by the paper: all five validated risk pathways are category-level disclosures rather than findings against this paper's own contribution. The region-specific SAR modelling belongs to a class of techniques that can promote algorithmic bias, but only under the condition that training data specific to one eco-region is applied to other regions or to formal/industrial areas — a condition this paper does not perform, since it trains dedicated models for each region. Likewise, the weakly supervised harvesting of labels from coarse Hansen maps is associated, in general, with population bias under the condition that models perform well only in data-rich areas and rely on noisy weak labels that may misclassify smallholder versus industrial disturbance, and such population bias is in turn linked (with strong category-level support) to resource allocation inequality in land-use and resource management contexts; however, the paper does not instantiate this chain. Finally, the disclosure that deep-learning disturbance detection could be used for law-enforcement targeting of logging — and thereby, through surreptitious surveillance, lead to location privacy violations in geoslavery-style automated monitoring — is an inferred, conditional category risk that this paper does not trigger; the work maps disturbances, but performs no surveillance or enforcement-targeting action.\n\nIn terms of mitigations, the paper's deliberate use of separate, region-tailored models for Paraguay and Mozambique works against the cross-region transfer condition that would activate the algorithmic bias pathway, which is a constructive design choice even if the underlying weak-label noise remains a documented general concern. Overall, the auditor's judgement is that this paper instantiates zero of the five validated risks: every pathway is a disclosure of risk associated with the broader class of SAR and weakly supervised disturbance-detection methods, conditional on triggering actions the paper does not take. Two of these disclosures rest on strong category-level grounding (the population-bias-to-resource-inequality and surveillance-to-privacy links), but because none is instantiated, none constitutes a finding against this work. The paper should therefore be regarded as raising no actually-instantiated ethical harm; its responsible course is to acknowledge these category-level risks and the conditions under which future deployments could activate them, particularly the smallholder-versus-industrial misclassification and any downstream enforcement use of its near-real-time maps.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (SAR-based deep learning disturbance detection applied across distinct eco-regions:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When training data is specific to one region or eco-region but applied to formal or industrial city areas / other regions)\n- (weakly supervised label harvesting from coarse Hansen forest-loss maps:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: when models perform well only in data-rich areas and rely on noisy weak labels that may misclassify smallholder vs. industrial disturbance)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n- (deep neural network disturbance detection used for law enforcement targeting of logging operations:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (surreptitious surveillance:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | disclosure>\n- (surreptitious surveillance:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (location privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of geoslavery and automated monitoring of individuals.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: SAR-based deep learning disturbance detection applied across distinct eco-regions, weakly supervised label harvesting from coarse Hansen forest-loss maps, deep neural network disturbance detection used for law enforcement targeting of logging operations\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic bias, population bias, surreptitious surveillance\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, location privacy violation",
