   "source": {
    "title": "Deep residential representations: Using unsupervised learning to unlock elevation data for geo-demographic prediction",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2022.03.015",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2022.03.015",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2022",
    "abstract": "LiDAR (short for “Light Detection And Ranging” or “Laser Imaging, Detection, And Ranging”) technology can be used to provide detailed three-dimensional elevation maps of urban and rural landscapes. The geographically granular and open-source nature of this data lends itself to an array of societal, organisational and business applications where geo-demographic type data is utilised. However, the complexity involved in processing this multi-dimensional data in raw form has thus far restricted its practical adoption. This paper proposes a series of convenient task-agnostic tile elevation embeddings to address this challenge, using recent advances from unsupervised Deep Learning. We test the potential of our embeddings by predicting seven English indices of deprivation (2019) for small geographies in the Greater London area. These indices cover a range of socio-economic outcomes and serve as a proxy for a wide variety of potential downstream tasks to which the embeddings can be applied. We consider the suitability of this data not just on its own but also as an auxiliary source of data in combination with demographic features, thus providing a realistic use case for the embeddings. Having trialled various model/embedding configurations, we find that our best performing embeddings lead to Root-Mean-Squared-Error (RMSE) improvements of up to 21% over using standard demographic features alone. We also demonstrate how our embedding pipeline, using Deep Learning combined with K-means"
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops an embedding pipeline that combines deep learning with K-means clustering applied to LiDAR data collected from the Greater London area, producing latent representations intended to serve as proxies for a range of socio-economic outcomes and downstream tasks, including deprivation prediction across multiple domains. The method touches ethics at several points: it groups spatial and non-spatial data into interpretable classes (urban, suburban, rural) and assigns deprivation profiles to these clusters; it trains on a single regional dataset; and its embeddings are explicitly positioned as proxies applicable to socio-economic resource allocation. The single point where the paper's own method actively performs an ethically relevant action is its subjective grouping of data via K-means clustering into coherent tile segments whose latent features are then interpreted and associated with social profiles.\n\nOn the causal reasoning, only one finding is genuinely instantiated by this paper. With strong confidence, the auditor finds that the paper's subjective grouping of spatial and non-spatial data through K-means clustering—coupled with the assignment of deprivation profiles to the resulting urban/suburban/rural classes—promotes subjective narrative reinforcement; this is directly grounded in the paper's own demonstration that its pipeline \"produces coherent tile segments which allow the latent embedding features to be interpreted,\" and in its characterization of clusters by fixed deprivation and education profiles. The remaining risks are disclosures only and are not triggered by this paper. The pipeline's reliance on machine learning datasets belongs to a class that, under conditions of encoded bias in deprivation prediction used for allocation, can promote discriminatory resource allocation and downstream deprivation of economic resources—but the paper does not instantiate this allocation step. Similarly, training on Greater London data without oversight of terrain diversity belongs to a category that can promote algorithmic and systematic discrimination against particular landscape types or population densities; however, the paper does not instantiate that harm, and notably observes that its error improvements were \"geographically dispersed and not concentrated in urban, suburban or rural areas.\" Finally, while subjective narrative reinforcement can in principle promote statistical gerrymandering and social-stereotype reinforcement when clusters are tied to fixed social profiles, that downstream impact is disclosed as a category risk rather than demonstrated as a realized harm in this work.\n\nIn terms of mitigations, the paper offers no explicit ethics-facing safeguards within these triples, though its own reported finding that error reductions are geographically dispersed rather than concentrated by area type works against the non-representativeness concern. The auditor's overall judgement is that of six causal triples, only one is actually instantiated by this paper's contribution—the subjective-grouping-to-narrative-reinforcement link—and it is well-grounded, supported by strong confidence and direct textual evidence of the clustering and interpretation step. The other five are at most category-level disclosures: the paper belongs to a class of methods that, under stated conditions of biased data, non-representative training, and the binding of clusters to social profiles, could promote discriminatory allocation, economic deprivation, systematic discrimination, and stereotype reinforcement, but it does not perform the triggering actions for any of these. Accordingly, the audit raises a single, conditional finding about interpretive over-attribution of social profiles to clustered segments, and treats the remaining risks purely as disclosures of risks this paper does not instantiate.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (biased machine learning datasets:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (discriminatory resource allocation:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Encoded biases in deprivation prediction used for resource allocation)\n- (discriminatory resource allocation:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (deprivation of economic resources:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Based on socioeconomic status when deprivation predictions misallocate interventions)\n- (ai systems trained on non-representative data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic discrimination:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When the embeddings trained on Greater London LiDAR lack oversight of data diversity across terrains)\n- (algorithmic discrimination:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systematic discrimination:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Systematic bias against particular landscape types or population densities)\n- (subjective spatial and non-spatial data grouping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (subjective narrative reinforcement:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: K-means clustering into urban/suburban/rural classes with assigned deprivation profiles)\n- (subjective narrative reinforcement:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (statistical gerrymandering and social stereotype reinforcement:EthicalImpact) [PsychologicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Associating clusters with fixed deprivation/social profiles)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: biased machine learning datasets, ai systems trained on non-representative data, subjective spatial and non-spatial data grouping\n  RiskMechanism: discriminatory resource allocation, algorithmic discrimination, subjective narrative reinforcement\n  EthicalImpact: deprivation of economic resources, systematic discrimination, statistical gerrymandering and social stereotype reinforcement",
