   "id": "044",
   "source": {
    "title": "Building use and mixed-use classification with a transformer-based network fusing satellite images and geospatial textual information",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113767",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113767",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Assigning detailed use categories to buildings is a challenging and relevant task in urban land use classification with applications in urban planning, digital city modelling and twinning. This study aims to provide the categorisation of buildings with detailed use information by considering the possibilities of mixed-use. Mixed-use combines different use forms, and serves as a new type of use category. We obtain attributive information by combining satellite imagery that reflects spatial information and textual information from publicly available point-of-interest data collected by citizens and available on online maps. We propose a multimodal transformer-based building-use classification method to capture and fuse these different data sources within an end-to-end learning workflow. We evaluate the effectiveness of our proposed method on four urban areas in China. Experiments show that the proposed method effectively maps building use according to eight types of fine-grain categories, with a Micro F 1 score equal to 80.9%, and a Macro F 1 score equal to 62% for Wuhan research area. The proposed method is able to harness the relationship between the features obtained from the different data sources and results in higher accuracy than the state-of-the-art fusion-based multimodal integration methods. The proposed method can effectively increase the attributive grain of building use resulting in high classification accuracy."
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops an AI-driven pipeline for building detection and classification from remote sensing data, supplemented with points-of-interest (POI) information, training a multimodal deep learning model to assign roof or building typologies across several cities. The principal point where the methodology touches ethics lies in its training data composition: the authors explicitly acknowledge that the number of samples for certain categories is too low to train the model effectively, and that some buildings lacking POI and difficult to interpret from imagery are assigned an \"Unknown\" category. These data-side characteristics—sample imbalance across infrastructure types and uneven class representation—constitute the concrete triggers that engage the audit.\n\nOn the basis of these triggers, the auditor records one instantiated finding. The paper's own method promotes the misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, a risk that the authors' own results substantiate: categories with more samples (such as \"R,\" \"B,\" and \"RB\") achieve markedly higher accuracy than under-represented categories, and the documented sample imbalance directly drives this disparity. This is a STRONG, instantiated finding, and it is reported as such, though it holds under the stated condition that the training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types—a condition the paper plainly meets. Beyond this, the remaining risks are disclosures of category-level concern that this paper does not itself instantiate. The misclassification mechanism could promote discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid, but only under the condition that roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status—an application this paper does not perform. Similarly, biased datasets can promote systematic discrimination when deployed in urban planning, and sampling bias toward dominant cultures can promote exclusion from knowledge production when data excludes vulnerable groups such as children, older adults, homeless individuals, or people with disabilities; the paper's cross-city accuracy degradation (lower results for cities other than Wuhan) is noted in connection with domain-transfer bias, but this is offered as a plausible, MODERATE, inferred association rather than a demonstrated harm. None of these downstream impacts is triggered by the paper's contribution, and each is reported strictly as a conditional, category-level disclosure rather than a finding against this work.\n\nThe auditor notes no affirmative mitigation measures embedded in the method; the most that can be said is that the authors are transparent about their data limitations, openly reporting the sample imbalance, the accuracy disparities across categories, and the \"Unknown\" assignments—a candor that is itself helpful for accountability. Overall, of the five validated triples, only one risk is actually instantiated by this paper—the sample-imbalance-driven misclassification of heterogeneous roof types—and that single finding is well-grounded, supported directly by the paper's own tables and accuracy comparisons. The remaining four are potential, condition-bound disclosures describing risks characteristic of this class of technique that the paper does not trigger. The auditor's judgement is therefore that this paper carries one substantiated, STRONG instantiated finding rooted in its training data, while its more serious downstream equal-rights impacts remain hypothetical and contingent on applications the paper neither undertakes nor endorses.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types)\n- (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status)\n- (biased machine learning datasets:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (systematic discrimination:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When used in urban planning applications)\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (sampling bias toward dominant cultures:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types)\n- (sampling bias toward dominant cultures:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (exclusion from knowledge production:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When data excludes children, older adults, homeless individuals, or people with disabilities.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data, biased machine learning datasets\n  RiskMechanism: misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, sampling bias toward dominant cultures\n  EthicalImpact: discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid, systematic discrimination, exclusion from knowledge production",
