   "id": "047",
   "source": {
    "title": "Progressive multi-task graph neural network with multi-dimensional spatial feature fusion for building age prediction",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2026.105290",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2026.105290",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Accurate acquisition of building age information is of significant importance for understanding urban conditions. However, existing building age prediction methods face several challenges, including insufficient consideration of multi-dimensional spatial features, imbalanced sample distribution, and inadequate extraction of deep semantic features. To address these issues, this study designed a progressive multi-task learning-based graph neural network (PMTGNN) framework. First, the study innovatively integrates multi-source geospatial data to construct a multi-dimensional feature indicator system encompassing building geometric scale, building visual scale, resident perception scale, and socioeconomic scale. Based on this, graph-structured node representations are constructed to achieve comprehensive integration of building-related features. Second, the study introduces two auxiliary tasks (building height estimation and building function classification) to enhance the model’s generalization capability under sample imbalance conditions through knowledge transfer. Third, the study designs a progressive learning strategy, which leverages the synergistic effects of expert modules and gating networks to guide the model in gradually learning high-level semantic features from low-level building geometric features. Finally, taking Changzhou as an empirical case study, the study trained the model using existing building age data and filled in the missing age information for 51,281 bu"
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops a graph neural network model (PMTGNN) for predicting building age from spatial and structural attributes, treating buildings as nodes within a graph constructed from spatial adjacency relationships and learning their representations through a shared GCN feature learner. The work touches ethics at two principal points. First, it relies on training data whose label completeness is not uniform across building types: the authors document that lower-rise and informally constructed buildings exhibit substantially higher rates of age-label missingness, and that this missingness is systematically—rather than randomly—associated with building characteristics and spatial context. Second, the method employs deep neural networks whose internal decision logic is opaque, a \"black-box\" property the authors explicitly engage by deploying GNNExplainer as a post-hoc explanation module to surface the features that drive the model's period predictions.\n\nIn terms of causal risk reasoning, only one finding is actually instantiated by this paper's contribution. The auditor finds, with strong grounding, that the paper's use of black-box deep neural networks promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability—this is inherent to the GCN-based architecture the study employs and is therefore an actual property of the method, not merely a category association. The remaining substantive risks are disclosures only. The reliance on non-representative data is associated, in general, with algorithmic discrimination and the perpetuation of discriminatory applications, but only under the stated condition that the machine learning workflow lacks oversight of data diversity; this paper does not instantiate that triggering action—on the contrary, it documents and analyzes the non-random missingness, and reports that the model retains strong recall (0.69 and 0.74) on severely under-represented edge categories such as Pre-1980 and Post-2020, demonstrating resistance to data imbalance rather than amplification of it. Likewise, the chain from algorithmic discrimination to systematic discrimination as an equal-rights concern, and the conditional link from opacity to safety risks in high-risk remote sensing applications, belong to risk classes this method could fall within, but the paper does not perform the actions that would realize them; these are reported here strictly as category-level disclosures.\n\nOn mitigation, the paper meaningfully addresses the one risk it does instantiate: GNNExplainer is applied to inhibit the transparency and explainability deficit by optimizing a soft mask over node features and graph structure to identify the minimal subset of features most responsible for each prediction, and this mitigation is treated as already neutralizing—rather than merely flagging—the opacity concern. The auditor's overall judgement is that this paper instantiates only one risk (the black-box transparency concern), and that risk is both strongly grounded and accompanied by a directly applied mitigation. The other four risk relationships are not triggered by the paper's own method: three are conditional category-level disclosures whose triggering conditions the paper does not meet—and in the data-diversity case actively counters through documentation and demonstrated robustness—while the transparency mitigation is confirmed as operative. There is, accordingly, no genuine harm narrative to assert against this paper beyond the inherent and mitigated opacity of deep models; the substantive discrimination and safety risks remain disclosures of what this class of techniques can do in general, not findings against this work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (ai systems trained on non-representative data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic discrimination:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When the machine learning workflow lacks oversight of data diversity)\n- (algorithmic discrimination:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systematic discrimination:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>\n- (ai systems trained on non-representative data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (perpetuation of discriminatory applications:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When the machine learning workflow lacks oversight of data diversity)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (GNNExplainer post-hoc explanation:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | n/a>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: ai systems trained on non-representative data, black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic discrimination, perpetuation of discriminatory applications, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: systematic discrimination, safety risks in critical missions\n  Mitigation: GNNExplainer post-hoc explanation",
