   "source": {
    "title": "Mapping invasive Opuntia stricta in Kenya's Drylands using explainable machine learning with time-series remote sensing and geographic context",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104867",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104867",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Opuntia stricta is a globally widespread invasive species that degrades dryland ecosystems and threatens pastoral livelihoods. Accurate, high-resolution distribution maps are essential for effective management, but its spectral similarity to native vegetation complicates remote sensing-based classification. We developed an interpretable Random Forest model, incorporating SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP), to map Opuntia stricta and co-occurring land cover types at 10 m resolution across heterogeneous arid and semi-arid lands in Laikipia County, Kenya. The model integrated monthly Sentinel-2 imagery, climate, topographic, landscape structural, and anthropogenic factors. Field surveys were combined with manual labeling using Google Maps and Street View to address annotation gaps in remote areas. Grid-based spatial blocking at multiple scales was used to reduce spatial autocorrelation and assess generalizability. The multi-temporal model achieved 0.91 overall accuracy and an F1-score of 0.92 for Opuntia stricta on the spatial validation set (100 m grid), and 0.86 accuracy with an F1-score of 0.85 on the independent test set, substantially outperforming single-month models (accuracy: 0.62–0.79; F1: 0.67–0.82), with February identified as the most informative single-time window. SHAP analysis identified July precipitation, population density and nighttime land surface temperatures as top predictors, linking invasion patterns to dry-season aridity, wet-season rainfall, and warm "
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops an interpretable Random Forest model, augmented with SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP), to map the invasive *Opuntia stricta* and co-occurring land cover types at 10 m resolution across arid and semi-arid lands in Laikipia County, Kenya. To do so, the modeling framework assembles 337 candidate variables spanning five categories—spectral, climatic, topographic, landscape structural, and anthropogenic—integrating monthly Sentinel-2 imagery with climate, topographic, landscape, and anthropogenic factors. The work touches ethics at several concrete points: it mosaics disparate geodata into new integrated information products; it converts population counts and OpenStreetMap building footprints into smoothed 10-m density surfaces and tests multiple grid sizes (50 m, 100 m, 500 m, 1000 m), directly engaging the modifiable areal unit problem; and it builds toward interpretability via SHAP.\n\nTurning to the causal reasoning, three risks are actually instantiated by this paper's method. First, as a strong finding, the practice of mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references promotes the unintentional disclosure of sensitive information—but only under the stated condition that combining seemingly unrelated datasets creates new information products; the paper's integration of 337 variables across five categories meets the triggering action, so this is reported as a conditional but grounded finding. Second, the modifiable areal unit problem is strongly instantiated as a source of spatial data bias, evidenced directly by the paper's resolution conversions via kernel density estimation and its testing of partition scales. Third, and favorably, the paper instantiates transparency as a mitigation that inhibits model opacity through its interpretable Random Forest and SHAP design. By contrast, four further risks remain only category-level disclosures that this paper does not trigger. The unintentional disclosure mechanism could in principle promote a group privacy violation if detailed demographic clusters became publicly accessible—relevant because invasion hotspots were concentrated near identifiable communities such as Dol-Dol and specific group ranches—but this paper does not instantiate that exposure. Likewise, biased machine learning datasets can promote social inequity when data is sparse in rural areas, a class-level concern the paper actively works against by combining field surveys with manual labeling to address annotation gaps in remote areas. The false center phenomenon's potential to cause misallocation of public resources, and the route from model opacity to spatial justice and accountability violations when planning decisions affect citizens, are similarly disclosed as associated risks rather than triggered ones; the latter two carry moderate confidence and should be read as plausible category associations, not findings against this work.\n\nIn terms of mitigations, the paper's central design choice—an interpretable model with SHAP explanations—is itself a strongly grounded, instantiated mitigation that directly counters the opacity risk, and its effort to fill annotation gaps in remote areas reduces the dataset-bias pathway it might otherwise have triggered. Overall, the auditor finds three risks actually instantiated by this paper, of which two are adverse (geodata mosaicking enabling sensitive disclosure, and MAUP-driven spatial bias) and one is protective (transparency). Both adverse instantiated findings are strongly grounded in the paper's own text and are appropriately conditional. The remaining four risks are merely disclosed as risks of the broader technique class and should not be read as charges against this paper; indeed, on at least the dataset-bias dimension the paper takes active steps in the opposite direction. The instantiated findings are therefore well-supported, narrowly scoped, and largely offset by the paper's interpretability commitments.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (unintentional disclosure of sensitive information:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When combining seemingly unrelated datasets creates new information products)\n- (unintentional disclosure of sensitive information:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (group privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: If detailed demographic clusters become accessible to the public)\n- (biased machine learning datasets:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (social inequity:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When data is sparse in rural areas or privileges dominant demographics)\n- (modifiable areal unit problem maup:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (spatial data bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>\n- (false center phenomenon:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (misallocation of public resources:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n- (transparency:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (model opacity and lack of interpretability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: when processes are made interpretable)\n- (model opacity and lack of interpretability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (spatial justice and accountability violations:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When impacting citizens' lives through planning decisions)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai, biased machine learning datasets, modifiable areal unit problem maup\n  RiskMechanism: unintentional disclosure of sensitive information, spatial data bias, false center phenomenon, model opacity and lack of interpretability\n  EthicalImpact: group privacy violation, social inequity, misallocation of public resources, spatial justice and accountability violations\n  Mitigation: transparency",
