   "id": "058",
   "source": {
    "title": "Spatially explicit accuracy assessment of deep learning-based, fine-resolution built-up land data in the United States",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2023.103469",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2023.103469",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Geospatial datasets derived from remote sensing data by means of machine learning methods are often based on probabilistic outputs of abstract nature, which are difficult to translate into interpretable measures. For example, the Global Human Settlement Layer GHS-BUILT-S2 product reports the probability of the presence of built-up areas in 2018 in a global 10 m × 10 m grid. However, practitioners typically require interpretable measures such as binary surfaces indicating the presence or absence of built-up areas or estimates of sub-pixel built-up surface fractions. Herein, we assess the relationship between the built-up probability in GHS-BUILT-S2 and reference built-up surface fractions derived from a highly reliable reference database for several regions in the United States. Furthermore, we identify a binarization threshold using an agreement maximization method that creates binary built-up land data from these built-up probabilities. These binary surfaces are input to a spatially explicit, scale-sensitive accuracy assessment which includes the use of a novel, visual-analytical tool which we call focal precision-recall signature plots. Our analysis reveals that a threshold of 0.5 applied to GHS-BUILT-S2 maximizes the agreement with binarized built-up land data derived from the reference built-up area fraction. We find high levels of accuracy (i.e., county-level F-1 scores of almost 0.8 on average) in the derived built-up areas, and consistently high accuracy along the rura"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper concerns the evaluation of binary human settlement data—surfaces distinguishing built-up from not-built-up areas—which serve as inputs to downstream geospatial tasks such as population disaggregation and analyses of urban morphology. The technical contribution centers on a spatially explicit, scale-sensitive accuracy assessment, including a novel visual-analytical tool the authors call focal precision–recall signature plots. The paper touches ethics at the intersection of two concerns: how classifier confidence varies across regions (with the authors noting that the GHS-BUILT-S2 surface may be more confident in detecting high-density structures, possibly due to spillover effects from impervious surfaces), and how performance is measured across the rural–urban gradient. These observations are the points at which the work engages questions of bias and fairness in settlement data.\n\nThe one risk actually instantiated by this paper's own method is, in fact, a mitigating one: the auditor finds, on strong grounds, that the paper's spatially explicit performance evaluation with hot/cold-spot detection inhibits the risk of evaluation bias hiding regional variability. By exposing where accuracy is biased across the rural–urban gradient through the signature plots, the paper actively works against masked regional error rather than introducing it. The remaining substantive risks are disclosures of category-level concern that this paper does not trigger. The use of deep learning models for population mapping belongs to a class that can promote population bias under conditions of spatial heterogeneity and varying neighborhood sizes where classifier confidence differs across regions, and such population bias can in turn promote resource allocation inequality when binary built-up surfaces are used as ancillary data for population disaggregation; both are flagged conditionally and as potential, not as findings against this paper. Likewise, the chain in which evaluation bias hiding regional variability can promote reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions—pertinent here because the analysis shows low F-1 accuracy occurs almost exclusively in low-density, rural areas—is a deployment-stage disclosure conditional on downstream use, not a harm this paper instantiates. Separately, the conventional, non-spatially-explicit aggregate metrics (precision, recall, F-score) that would promote hidden regional variability are explicitly not triggered, because the paper argues against overly generalized accuracy metrics and demonstrates the need for spatially explicit assessment.\n\nBy way of mitigation, the paper's central methodological contribution is itself the remedy: its spatially explicit, scale-sensitive evaluation and signature-plot tooling directly counter the masking of regional error that aggregate metrics produce, and the paper explicitly declines to rely on those generalized metrics. In the auditor's overall judgement, of the five validated triples, only one is actually instantiated by this paper—and it is a strongly grounded mitigation rather than a harm. Three triples are disclosures of category-level risk (population bias, resource allocation inequality, and reduced reliability in underserved regions) that the paper does not itself perform, and one is a risk the paper neutralizes. Accordingly, the auditor finds no ethical harm actually instantiated by this paper's contribution; on the contrary, the paper's well-grounded methodological choice works to surface and inhibit exactly the kind of spatially uneven, fairness-relevant error that the disclosed category risks describe.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (deep learning models for population mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Under conditions of spatial heterogeneity and varying neighborhood sizes; classifier confidence varies across regions)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management; binary built-up surfaces used as ancillary data for population disaggregation)\n- (spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: By exposing where accuracy is biased across the rural-urban gradient using focal precision-recall signature plots)\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of human settlement data for downstream geospatial tasks; rural areas show lower accuracy)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: deep learning models for population mapping, non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score\n  RiskMechanism: population bias, evaluation bias hiding regional variability\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions\n  Mitigation: spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection",
