   "source": {
    "title": "Most complicated lock pattern-based seismological signal framework for automated earthquake detection",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2023.103297",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2023.103297",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Background Seismic signals record earthquakes and also noise from different sources. The influence of noise makes it difficult to interpret seismograph signals correctly. This study aims to develop a computationally lightweight, accurate, and explainable machine learning model for the automated detection of seismogram signals that could serve as an effective warning system for earthquake prediction. Material and method We developed a handcrafted model for earthquake detection using a balanced dataset of 5001 earthquakes and 5001 non-earthquake signal samples. The model included multilevel feature extraction, selector-based feature selection, classification, and post-processing. Input signals were decomposed using tunable Q wave transform and fed to a statistical and textural feature extractor based on the most complicated lock pattern (MCLP). Four feature selectors were used to choose the most valuable features for the support vector machine classifier. Additionally, voted vectors were generated using iterative hard majority voting. Finally, the best model was chosen using a greedy algorithm. Results The presented self-organized MCLP-based feature engineering model yielded 96.82% classification accuracy with 10-fold cross-validation using the seismic signal dataset. Conclusions Our model attained high seismological signal detection performance comparable with more computationally expensive deep learning models. Our handcrafted explainable feature engineering model is computat"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops a computationally lightweight, accurate, and explainable machine learning model for the automated detection of seismogram signals, intended to serve as a warning system for earthquake prediction. The reported method is a self-organized MCLP-based feature engineering model that achieved 96.82% classification accuracy under 10-fold cross-validation on a seismic signal dataset. The point at which this work touches ethical territory lies in its construction of training data: the authors built a balanced dataset of over 10,000 observations by selecting the first 5,001 earthquake and the first 5,001 non-earthquake seismogram signals from the Len-DB database. Because this is a binary earthquake/non-earthquake classifier potentially deployed as a warning system, its data-selection choices and misclassification behaviour are the relevant triggers for examination.\n\nIn terms of causal risk reasoning, it is important to state at the outset that none of the validated triples is INSTANTIATED by this paper — all four are POTENTIAL, category-level disclosures rather than actual findings against this work. The first disclosure is that AI systems trained on non-representative data can promote algorithmic discrimination, but this holds only under the condition that the seismogram training subset is geographically unspecified and uses only the smallest subset of Len-DB; while strongly grounded as a category concern, this paper does not perform the action that would instantiate it. Relatedly, such algorithmic discrimination can promote systematic discrimination (an equal-rights concern) only if misclassification rates differ across regions with differing seismic signal characteristics — again a conditional, non-triggered disclosure. A third disclosure notes that non-representative training data can perpetuate discriminatory applications specifically when a deployed binary classifier misclassifies a real earthquake as noise, and a fourth observes that limitations of traditional supervision methods can promote physical harm when dealing with complex datasets and evolving environments. Each of these is a recognized risk of the broader class of techniques to which this method belongs, but in every case the paper does not itself instantiate the triggering action, so none can be reported as a finding against this paper.\n\nNo specific mitigations are recorded in the validated triples, though it is worth noting the paper's stated emphasis on an explainable model and its use of a deliberately balanced dataset, which bear on the data-representativeness concerns. Overall, the auditor's judgement is that this paper instantiates zero of the four identified risks: all four are STRONG-confidence but POTENTIAL, meaning they are well-grounded as category-level disclosures yet are not triggered by this paper's own contribution, and three of the four are further bounded by explicit conditions (geographically unspecified subsets, region-dependent misclassification rates, or deployment-time misclassification of a real earthquake) that are not shown to obtain here. The auditor therefore finds no ethical risk actually instantiated by this paper's contribution; the findings are at most disclosures of risks inherent to data-driven seismic classifiers, and the paper itself does not perform the actions that would convert them into harms.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (ai systems trained on non-representative data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic discrimination:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When the seismogram training subset is geographically unspecified and uses only the smallest subset of the Len-DB database)\n- (algorithmic discrimination:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systematic discrimination:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: If misclassification rates differ across regions with different seismic signal characteristics)\n- (ai systems trained on non-representative data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (perpetuation of discriminatory applications:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When a binary earthquake/non-earthquake classifier is deployed as a warning system and misclassifies a real earthquake as noise)\n- (limitations of traditional supervision methods:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (physical harm:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When dealing with complex datasets and evolving environments.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: ai systems trained on non-representative data\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic discrimination, perpetuation of discriminatory applications, limitations of traditional supervision methods\n  EthicalImpact: systematic discrimination, physical harm",
