   "source": {
    "title": "Predicting Household Income with Sentinel and Street View Imagery: A Comparative Study across Amsterdam, Sydney, and New York",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104828",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104828",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "In the context of urbanisation and growing disparities, timely and detailed spatial data on income inequality in cities is essential. We combined satellite imagery with streetlevel photographs provided by Google Street View to reveal the spatial distribution of household income. For this, we suggest a harmonised framework for median household income modelling based on deconstructing landscape patterns using a machine-learning approach, applied across three ’global cities’: Amsterdam, New York, and Sydney. First, we classified Sentinel-1 and Sentinel-2 mosaics and Google Street View scenes to detect functional elements of the built environment. Second, we calculated spatial indices for Sentinel imagery and visual indices for Google Street View scenes to characterise the urban landscape. Third, by combining various indicators, we trained city-specific income prediction models according to ground truth census data. The correlation between actual and predicted income in New York and Sydney reached 0.76 and 0.78, respectively. The accuracy of income prediction in Amsterdam reached 51.13%. We revealed relationships between spatial indicators of landscape patterns and spatial income distribution and recommend using Sentinel-1 and Sentinel-2 imagery as the primary data choice for income modelling in datarestricted regions. Google Street View data can be used complementarily when available."
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops a machine learning workflow that classifies Sentinel-1 and Sentinel-2 satellite mosaics together with Google Street View scenes in order to detect functional elements of the built environment and, ultimately, to reveal the spatial distribution of household income across cities such as Amsterdam, New York, and Greater Sydney. The point at which this work touches ethics is precisely its core technical operation: the mosaicking of disparate geodata using shared spatial references. By combining satellite imagery with street-level photographs and aligning these to fine-grained statistical grids (for Amsterdam, the official 100×100 m CBS grid), the paper's method fuses seemingly unrelated datasets into new information products keyed to socioeconomic status.\n\nThe single instantiated audit finding follows directly from this design. With STRONG confidence, the auditor finds that the paper's own mosaicking of disparate geodata promotes the unintentional disclosure of sensitive information, under the condition that combining unrelated datasets creates new information products — a condition this paper meets by construction when it derives income distribution from fused imagery. This is stated as an actual finding against the paper. The remaining risks are disclosures only, not findings. The onward step from unintentional disclosure to a group privacy violation is POTENTIAL and conditional (only if detailed demographic clusters become publicly accessible); this paper does not perform that publication step, so it belongs to a class that can raise group privacy harms without instantiating them. Similarly, the concerns around AI systems trained on non-representative data — that they can promote discriminatory applications and algorithmic discrimination, and that such discrimination can in turn cause deprivation of economic resources based on socioeconomic status or ethnicity — are all POTENTIAL. The paper candidly notes limits to transferability beyond high-income countries and a tendency of its models to regress toward the mean (underestimating very high and overestimating very low incomes, with false greenery–income effects in social-housing and peripheral areas), but these are surfaced as acknowledged limitations of a category-level risk rather than as harms the paper actively enacts.\n\nOn mitigation, the paper does take a concrete protective step: it downgrades map spatial resolution by publishing grid cells only for areas with at least five residents or five residential houses, which INHIBITS the group privacy violation risk. This triple is NOT_TRIGGERED, meaning the paper already neutralizes that pathway rather than raising it. In overall judgement, of the six validated triples only one is actually instantiated by this paper's contribution — the STRONG unintentional-disclosure finding tied to geodata mosaicking — and it is well-grounded in the paper's own text. Four further triples are disclosures of category-level risk that this paper does not trigger, and one reflects an active mitigation. The auditor therefore records a single, well-substantiated instantiated finding, conditional on the creation of new fused information products, against an otherwise transparent paper that discloses its representativeness limitations and applies a privacy-preserving resolution threshold.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (unintentional disclosure of sensitive information:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When combining seemingly unrelated datasets creates new information products)\n- (unintentional disclosure of sensitive information:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (group privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: If detailed demographic clusters become accessible to the public)\n- (downgrading map spatial resolution:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (group privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When handling sensitive applications like slum mapping)\n- (ai systems trained on non-representative data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (perpetuation of discriminatory applications:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When the machine learning workflow lacks oversight of data diversity)\n- (ai systems trained on non-representative data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic discrimination:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When the machine learning workflow lacks oversight of data diversity)\n- (algorithmic discrimination:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (deprivation of economic resources:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Based on socioeconomic status or ethnicity)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai, ai systems trained on non-representative data\n  RiskMechanism: unintentional disclosure of sensitive information, perpetuation of discriminatory applications, algorithmic discrimination\n  EthicalImpact: group privacy violation, deprivation of economic resources\n  Mitigation: downgrading map spatial resolution",
