     "source": "Transactions in GIS - 2023 - Xing - The challenges of integrating explainable artificial intelligence into GeoAI.pdf",
     "content": "or group of models (e.g., Decision  Tree). Model- agnostic approaches do not depend on the structure of the model itself but base explanations on  the inputs and outputs of XAI (e.g., SHAP and LIME). Then there is the when and where one applies XAI: ante hoc  XAI (attribution to inputs/outputs in the pre-  modeling phase) and post hoc XAI (post-  modeling phase, e.g., LIME).  Researchers also distinguish between white-  and black-  box methods; the former concerns AI models that are  simple and self- explanatory and the latter considers opaque models and data handling prevalent in DNN (Dwivedi  et al., 2023). All are used in GeoAI, as will be seen below. The use of XAI within GeoAI is still quite young (e.g., Xing & Sieber, 2021). Table 1 Column 3 summarizes  approaches used in GeoAI as well as other XAI methods that GeoAI has yet to consider. Current developments  of GeoXAI focus on interpreting performance issues of GeoAI (e.g., classification accuracy). For example, Luo  et al. (2021) combined integrated gradients (IGs) and Global Attribution Mapping, a type of salience mapping,  to select the most suitable (i.e., the highest detection accuracy) backbone network architectures for aircraft de - tection from remotely sensed imagery datasets. Their work exemplifies the challenges in integrating geographic  knowledge into the use of XAI (e.g., location, scale, and neighborhoods) in aircraft detection with DNN. Because  their DNN is a toggle (i.e., plane yes or no), a false negative might be the locational adjacency of ground-  based  vehicles parked near airplanes. The chosen XAI may not sufficiently account for the false negatives or positives.  XAI approaches Description Example algorithm  used for GeoAI Source Deconvolution  explanations Mapping feature attributions in  intermediate layers back to  the input feature space using  gradients N/A N/A Permutation  explanations Calculating the change of prediction  error for the model after users  shuffle features"
