   "id": "073",
   "source": {
    "title": "Semi-supervised water tank detection to support vector control of emerging infectious diseases transmitted by Aedes Aegypti",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2023.103304",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2023.103304",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "The disease transmitting mosquito Aedes Aegypti is an increasing global threat. It breeds in small artificial containers such as rainwater tanks and can be characterized by a short flight range. The resulting high spatial variability of abundance is challenging to model. Therefore, we tested an approach to map water tank density as a spatial proxy for urban Aedes Aegypti habitat suitability. Water tank density mapping was performed by a semi-supervised self-training approach based on open accessible satellite imagery for the city of Rio de Janeiro. We ran a negative binomial generalized linear regression model to evaluate the statistical significance of water tank density for modeling inner-urban Aedes Aegypti distribution measured by an entomological surveillance system between January 2019 and December 2021. Our proposed semi-supervised model outperformed a supervised model for water tank detection with respect to the F1-score by 22%. Water tank density was a significant predictor for the mean eggs per trap rate of Aedes Aegypti. This shows the potential of the proposed indicator to enrich urban entomological surveillance systems to plan more targeted vector control interventions, presumably leading to less infectious rates of dengue, Zika, and chikungunya in the future."
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops an AI-driven pipeline for detecting and classifying water tanks from remote sensing imagery, applied to the city of Rio de Janeiro, where the authors manually labeled 2,000 water tanks in favelas and another 2,000 in residential areas for training. The stated downstream purpose is to enrich urban entomological surveillance systems and plan more targeted vector-control interventions against dengue, Zika, and chikungunya. The work touches on ethics at several points: the classification of heterogeneous roof and infrastructure typologies, the use of self-supervised self-training (SSST) with high-confidence pseudo labels, and the reliance on aggregate, non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics (precision, recall, and F1-score) to report model performance.\n\nTurning to the causal risk reasoning, only one triple is actually instantiated by this paper's method. The auditor finds, with strong grounding, that the paper's reliance on non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics — reporting a single overall F1-score of 0.84 averaged across all test labels — instantiates the mechanism of evaluation bias that can hide regional variability in model performance. This is a genuine finding against the paper's methodology: performance across all five detection models was assessed only through aggregate precision, recall, and F1. However, its downstream ethical consequence — reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions — remains a POTENTIAL, category-level disclosure conditioned on the deployment of geoparsers for downstream tasks, and is not itself triggered here. Similarly, the remaining risks are disclosures rather than findings. The AI-driven building/tank detection method belongs to a class that can, under conditions of training-data imbalance for specific infrastructure types, promote misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, which in turn — only when roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status — could feed into resource-allocation inequality and discriminatory allocation of humanitarian aid. These are real category-level concerns, made salient by the paper's own observation that water tanks appear more frequently in socially weaker areas such as favelas, but the triples classify them as POTENTIAL: this paper does not instantiate the discriminatory allocation itself. Likewise, the association between recursive training on synthetic data and \"GeoAI collapse,\" and its knock-on systemic bias against rare or minority place-based features, is a disclosed but not-triggered concern.\n\nOn mitigations, the paper takes a concrete step against the recursive-training collapse risk: it screens pseudo labels by using only high-confidence water-tank predictions (an 80% confidence threshold) before folding them back into fine-tuning. The auditor therefore treats the GeoAI-collapse mechanism as NOT_TRIGGERED — the paper acts to neutralize rather than instantiate it, though residual false negatives (e.g., tanks in shade) are acknowledged. Overall, of the seven validated triples, only one is actually instantiated by this paper's contribution — the aggregate-evaluation-metric bias — and that single finding is strongly grounded in the paper's own reported methodology. The remaining five are disclosures of category-level risk that this paper does not trigger, and one is a risk the paper explicitly guards against. The auditor's judgement is thus that this paper's contribution instantiates a narrow, well-grounded evaluation-transparency concern, while the more serious equity harms around discriminatory resource allocation remain disclosed possibilities tied to hypothetical downstream use rather than findings against the work itself.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types)\n- (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status)\n- (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status)\n- (recursive training on synthetic geospatial data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (geoai collapse:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When AI-generated images or model-derived analytical outputs are used as training data for subsequent generations without screening.)\n- (geoai collapse:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systemic bias against rare or minority place-based features:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: During multigenerational training cycles where models amplify dominant statistical patterns and filter out rare features.)\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of geoparsers for downstream geospatial tasks)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data, recursive training on synthetic geospatial data, non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score\n  RiskMechanism: misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, geoai collapse, evaluation bias hiding regional variability\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid, systemic bias against rare or minority place-based features, reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions",
