   "source": {
    "title": "TLNet: A deep learning framework for tree detection in forest point clouds using multi-layered forest structure",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.02.002",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.02.002",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Individual-tree detection underpins forest inventory, growth monitoring, silvicultural planning, and disturbance assessment. Light Detection and Ranging (LiDAR) provides the 3D structure needed for this task; however, severe occlusion, irregular and range-dependent point density, and platform-dependent sampling geometry and visibility still hinder consistent performance across sites and sensors. We present Tree-Layer Network (TLNet), a deep learning framework that addresses these challenges by slicing forest point clouds into a stack of thin horizontal slabs that mirror the natural multi-layered organization of forest strata (understory, midstory, and overstory). Within each slab, 3D points are embedded via sparse-voxel convolutions and mapped onto a 2D grid of local features. To capture vertical context, TLNet fuses these grid feature maps in two directions: a bottom-up pass that propagates stable stem and lower-crown cues upward, and a top-down pass that injects overstory information downward. Learnable scalar gates adaptively re-weight each slab’s grid features to emphasize the most informative forest layers, and a lightweight decoder predicts a tree-location heatmap and coordinate offsets for precise localization. To mitigate limited real-world labels, we pre-train TLNet on fully labeled synthetic forests and fine-tune on datasets from three LiDAR platforms: terrestrial laser scanning, mobile laser scanning, and unmanned aerial vehicle-borne laser scanning. Across both co"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThe paper under review introduces TLNet, a tree-detection model evaluated across coniferous- and deciduous-dominated sites, where it attains an average F1 score greater than 0.88 and outperforms several point-based deep-learning backbones and platform-specialized heuristic detectors. The point at which this work touches ethics concerns the design of its performance evaluation: whether detection quality is reported as a single aggregate corpus-wide score or is instead broken down by subpopulation, stratum, and platform. This is the relevant trigger because the granularity of evaluation determines whether uneven performance across regions or forest strata is exposed or concealed.\n\nOn the causal reasoning, the auditor finds that this paper does not instantiate the central risk of evaluation bias that hides regional variability. Although a non-spatially-explicit metric — an aggregate F1 across a whole corpus — is the kind of feature that can promote such bias, that mechanism only holds under the condition that performance is measured solely as an overall score rather than stratified by region or subpopulation, and this paper does the opposite. Consequently, the downstream ethical concern that such hidden variability could reduce reliability and fairness in underserved regions during deployment for forest-inventory or silvicultural tasks remains, though strongly reasoned in the general case, only a category-level disclosure: this paper does not perform the triggering action, so it is not raised as a finding against the work. Indeed, the paper reports reduced F1 for understory trees — consistent with occlusion and sparser returns — while noting these still maintain very small localization errors (stratum-averaged MAE of 0.036 m), demonstrating precisely the disaggregated transparency whose absence would drive the risk.\n\nThe mitigation present here is the paper's own decision to conduct a spatially-explicit, stratified evaluation, reporting results separately for the two strata exactly as defined in the reference dataset and per platform, thereby exposing where the detector performs worse (understory versus overstory, broadleaf versus coniferous). With moderate confidence, the auditor treats this stratified reporting as an instantiated mitigation that actively inhibits the evaluation-bias mechanism. Overall, of the three validated triples, none constitutes an instantiated harm against this paper: one describes a mechanism the paper does not trigger, one is a strongly-reasoned but merely potential category-level disclosure that this paper does not instantiate, and the single instantiated triple is a mitigation rather than a risk. The auditor's judgement is therefore that this paper instantiates no ethical harm from its contribution; on the contrary, its disaggregated evaluation practice affirmatively addresses the very risk that non-spatially-explicit reporting would otherwise raise.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics (aggregate F1 across whole corpus):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus rather than stratified by subpopulation or region)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of the detector for downstream geospatial (forest inventory/silvicultural) tasks)\n- (spatially-explicit / stratified performance evaluation (per-stratum, per-platform reporting):Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: By exposing where the detector performs worse (e.g., understory vs overstory, broadleaf vs coniferous))\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics (aggregate F1 across whole corpus)\n  RiskMechanism: evaluation bias hiding regional variability\n  EthicalImpact: reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions\n  Mitigation: spatially-explicit / stratified performance evaluation (per-stratum, per-platform reporting)",
