   "source": {
    "title": "Overview of SMOS performance in terms of global soil moisture monitoring after six years in operation",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2016.02.042",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2016.02.042",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2016",
    "abstract": "The Soil Moisture and Ocean Salinity satellite (SMOS) was launched in November 2009 and started delivering data in January 2010. The commissioning phase ended in May 2010. Subsequently, the satellite has been in operation for over six years while the retrieval algorithms from Level 1 (L1) to Level 2 (L2) underwent significant evolutions as knowledge improved. Moreover, other approaches for retrieval at L2 over land were investigated while Level 3 (L3) and Level 4 (L4) were initiated. In this paper, these improvements were assessed by inter-comparisons of the current L2 (V620) against the previous version (V551) and new products (using neural networks referred to as SMOS-NN) and L3 (referred to as SMOS-L3). In addition, a global evaluation of different SMOS soil moisture (SM) products (SMOS-L2, SMOS-L3, and SMOS-NN) was performed comparing products with those of model simulations and other satellites. Finally, all products were evaluated against in situ measurements of soil moisture (SM). To achieve such a goal a set of metrics to evaluate different satellite products are suggested. The study demonstrated that the V620 shows a significant improvement (including those at L1 improving L2) with respect to the earlier version V551. Results also show that neural network based approaches can often yield excellent results over areas where other products are poor. Finally, global comparison indicates that SMOS behaves very well when compared to other sensors/approaches and gives consi"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThe paper under review develops a machine learning approach to soil moisture retrieval from SMOS (Soil Moisture and Ocean Salinity) observations, specifically employing a feed-forward neural network (the SMOS-NN) for operational near-real-time retrieval. As described in its own text, this method takes SMOS-L3 brightness temperatures, averaged in 5°-width incidence angle bins and grouped with other information sources, as inputs following an approach similar to Rodriguez-Fernandez et al. (2015). Once trained, these neural networks are very fast to apply and form the basis of an algorithm to retrieve soil moisture in near-real-time. The point at which this work touches ethics is its reliance on the black-box nature of deep neural networks, a technical feature that is generically associated with limitations in transparency and explainability, and its potential feeding of operational products used downstream in high-stakes applications.\n\nTurning to the causal risk reasoning, it is essential to distinguish what this paper actually instantiates from what it merely inherits as a member of a technique class. Both validated triples are tagged as POTENTIAL, meaning that while the SMOS-NN belongs to a category of methods where these risks are recognized, the paper does not itself perform the triggering action that would convert them into audit findings. As a disclosure, the black-box nature of the feed-forward neural network can promote a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, and that opacity can in turn promote safety risks in critical missions — but only conditionally, specifically in high-risk remote sensing applications such as drought and famine early warning or flood forecasting that depend on SMOS soil moisture products. These are strongly grounded as category-level associations, yet neither is instantiated by this paper's contribution: the paper does not demonstrate that its retrieval is deployed in such a safety-critical decision chain, nor does it exhibit an opacity failure of its own. Accordingly, neither risk can be asserted as a finding against this paper; both remain conditional disclosures of what the wider class of black-box neural retrieval methods can raise.\n\nNo mitigations are recorded among the validated triples, and no risk is tagged as NOT_TRIGGERED, so the paper is neither shown to neutralize these concerns nor to actively worsen them. The overall auditor's judgement is that this paper instantiates zero ethical risks through its own method: of the two validated triples, both are disclosures at the category level rather than audit findings, and while each is strongly grounded as a general association, that grounding pertains to the technique class and to conditional downstream applications, not to any action this paper performs. The transparency and safety concerns are therefore reported here purely as class-level disclosures — the paper appears ethics-silent on these matters, and no harm narrative specific to its contribution is warranted.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: SMOS-NN feed-forward neural network used for operational near-real-time soil moisture retrieval)\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications such as drought/famine early warning and flood forecasting that depend on SMOS soil moisture products)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions",
