   "id": "080",
   "source": {
    "title": "Large scale multi-layer fuel load characterization in tropical savanna using GEDI spaceborne lidar data",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2021.112764",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2021.112764",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2022",
    "abstract": "Quantifying fuel load over large areas is essential to support integrated fire management initiatives in fire-prone regions to preserve carbon stock, biodiversity and ecosystem functioning. It also allows a better understanding of global climate regulation as a potential carbon sink or source. Large area assessments usually require data from spaceborne remote sensors, but most of them cannot measure the vertical variability of vegetation structure, which is required for accurately measuring fuel loads and defining management interventions. The recently launched NASA's Global Ecosystem Dynamics Investigation (GEDI) full-waveform lidar sensor holds potential to meet this demand. However, its capability for estimating fuel load has yet not been evaluated. In this study, we developed a novel framework and tested machine learning models for predicting multi-layer fuel load in the Brazilian tropical savanna (i.e., Cerrado biome) using GEDI data. First, lidar data were collected using an unnamed aerial vehicle (UAV). The flights were conducted over selected sample plots in distinct Cerrado vegetation formations (i.e., grassland, savanna, forest) where field measurements were conducted to determine the load of surface, herbaceous, shrubs and small trees, woody fuels and the total fuel load. Subsequently, GEDI-like full-waveforms were simulated from the high-density UAV-lidar 3-D point clouds from which vegetation structure metrics were calculated and correlated to field-derived fuel "
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThe paper develops a machine-learning workflow—based on a Random Forest algorithm tuned via 5-fold cross-validation—to estimate and map fuel loads across the entire Cerrado biome using GEDI spaceborne LiDAR data. Several aspects of this methodology touch on ethics-relevant territory. The model is evaluated using aggregate, non-spatially-explicit metrics (R², RMSE, mean difference), and predictions are extrapolated to biome-scale fuel maps generated from all available on-orbit GEDI footprints. The workflow also processes complex, multidimensional geographic variables (canopy structure, understory strata), and the resulting products are relevant to fire management and wildfire planning contexts. Each of these features constitutes a point of contact with the risk categories catalogued below, though—critically—none of the identified triples is instantiated as an actual harm by this paper.\n\nTurning to the causal risk reasoning, it must be stated plainly at the outset that the auditor found **no ethical risk actually instantiated by this paper's contribution**: all seven validated triples are tagged POTENTIAL, meaning they describe category-level risks associated with this class of technique rather than triggering actions performed by this paper. As disclosures, the reasoning runs as follows. The reliance on aggregate evaluation metrics belongs to a class that can promote evaluation bias hiding regional variability, but only under the condition that performance is measured solely as a single overall corpus score; this in turn is associated, in the deployment of models for downstream biome-scale tasks, with reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions—yet this paper does not instantiate that deployment harm. Similarly, models trained on non-representative data can promote spatial data bias where the workflow lacks oversight of data diversity, and such bias can conditionally promote social inequity when fuel maps guide resource-limited fire management; again, these are conditional, category-level associations the paper does not itself trigger. The black-box processing of complex geographic variables is associated with inadvertent inferential error where transparent guardrails are absent, and such error could conditionally raise safety risks when fuel estimates feed safety-critical wildfire planning—but this is a moderate-confidence, potential linkage, not a finding against the paper. None of these should be read as an assertion that this paper causes fairness harm, spatial bias, social inequity, or physical safety risk; they are disclosures of the risk landscape surrounding the technique.\n\nOn mitigations, the paper does take a constructive step that the audit can note favorably: it quantifies the uncertainty of fuel load predictions in each cell, accounting for footprint variability, RF algorithmic uncertainty, and RF lack of fit. This mitigation is strongly grounded and inhibits the unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical remote sensing applications—directly consistent with the integrity and uncertainty-reporting principles emphasized in responsible AI4EO practice. In overall judgement, of the seven triples reviewed, zero are instantiated as audit findings against this paper and all seven are disclosures of category-level risk that the paper does not trigger; moreover, the paper affirmatively incorporates uncertainty quantification, addressing one of the most safety-relevant risk mechanisms. The auditor therefore concludes that this paper instantiates no ethical harm, that the surrounding risks are well-documented but remain conditional and disclosure-only, and that the paper's uncertainty reporting represents a genuine, well-grounded mitigation rather than an ethics-silent omission.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of models for downstream biome-scale geospatial tasks)\n- (ai systems trained on non-representative data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (spatial data bias:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When the machine learning workflow lacks oversight of data diversity)\n- (spatial data bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (social inequity:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When fuel maps guide resource-limited fire management)\n- (black-box spatial analysis:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When complex multidimensional geographic variables are processed without transparent guardrails)\n- (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When fuel estimates feed safety-critical wildfire planning)\n- (uncertainty quantification:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score, ai systems trained on non-representative data, black-box spatial analysis\n  RiskMechanism: evaluation bias hiding regional variability, spatial data bias, inadvertent inferential error, unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks\n  EthicalImpact: reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions, social inequity, safety risks in critical missions\n  Mitigation: uncertainty quantification",
