   "id": "081",
   "source": {
    "title": "Estimating leaf mass per area and equivalent water thickness based on leaf optical properties: Potential and limitations of physical modeling and machine learning",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2018.11.002",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2018.11.002",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2019",
    "abstract": "Leaf mass per area (LMA) and leaf equivalent water thickness (EWT) are key leaf functional traits providing information for many applications including ecosystem functioning modeling and fire risk management. In this paper, we investigate two common conclusions generally made for LMA and EWT estimation based on leaf optical properties in the near-infrared (NIR) and shortwave infrared (SWIR) domains: (1) physically-based approaches estimate EWT accurately and LMA poorly, while (2) statistically-based and machine learning (ML) methods provide accurate estimates of both LMA and EWT. Using six experimental datasets including broadleaf species samples of &gt;150 species collected over tropical, temperate and boreal ecosystems, we compared the performances of a physically-based method (PROSPECT model inversion) and a ML algorithm (support vector machine regression, SVM) to infer EWT and LMA based on leaf reflectance and transmittance. We assessed several merit functions to invert PROSPECT based on iterative optimization and investigated the spectral domain to be used for optimal estimation of LMA and EWT. We also tested several strategies to select the training samples used by the SVM, in order to investigate the generalization ability of the derived regression models. We evidenced that using spectral information from 1700 to 2400 nm leads to strong improvement in the estimation of EWT and LMA when performing a PROSPECT inversion, decreasing the LMA and EWT estimation errors by 55%"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper addresses the estimation of leaf functional traits — specifically leaf mass per area (LMA) and leaf equivalent water thickness (EWT) — by comparing machine learning regression approaches against physically-based PROSPECT model inversion. Its ethical contact points arise directly from its methodological choices: it trains machine learning regression models (including SVM) on non-representative public leaf datasets such as LOPEX and ANGERS, and it works with leaf optical datasets that were collected by different operators, using different devices and under differing acquisition conditions. These data-provenance and generalization concerns are the primary sites where the paper's technical work touches on ethics, as the authors themselves foreground the diversity of acquisition sources as a possible source of bias.\n\nTurning to the causal risk reasoning, three findings are actually instantiated by this paper's own method. With moderate confidence, the auditor finds that the paper's use of regression models trained on non-representative public datasets can promote misleading models that yield incorrect predictions, but only under the stated condition that the regression model is applied to data fully independent from the training set — a limitation the paper explicitly evidences through its comparison of sampling strategies for SVM, which showed limited generalization ability. Also with moderate confidence, the heterogeneity of the leaf optical datasets — collected by different operators and devices — is found to promote the same risk of incorrect predictions, conditional on a machine learning workflow that lacks oversight of data diversity across acquisition sources; the paper itself acknowledges this diversity as a source of bias. Separately, and as a disclosure only, the strongly-supported category-level link between misleading predictions and safety risks in critical missions (such as fire risk management) is *not* instantiated by this paper. That triple is flagged POTENTIAL: while incorrect trait estimates could in principle propagate into safety-critical geoscience tasks, this paper does not deploy its models in any such mission, and so this must be reported only as a class-level risk that the paper does not itself trigger.\n\nOn the mitigation side, the paper demonstrates a concrete corrective: restricting PROSPECT inversion to the 1700–2400 nm spectral domain inhibits the risk of misleading predictions, a mitigation the authors quantify as reducing LMA and EWT estimation errors by 55% and 33% respectively, and which requires no training data. This directly counters the generalization weakness identified above, since the inversion approach in an appropriate spectral domain is shown to outperform SVM trained on experimental data. In overall judgement, of the four validated triples, three are instantiated as genuine audit findings and one is merely a disclosure of category-level safety risk that this paper does not enact. None of the instantiated findings reach strong confidence — all three are moderately grounded and appropriately qualified by their stated conditions — and, importantly, the paper does not merely raise these data-diversity and generalization risks but supplies and empirically validates a mitigation that meaningfully addresses them. The paper is therefore ethically self-aware within its scope, with its residual risks conditional and partially neutralized rather than left open.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (machine learning regression models trained on non-representative public leaf datasets (LOPEX, ANGERS):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When the regression model is applied on data fully independent from the training set)\n- (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: safety-critical geoscience and remote sensing tasks such as fire risk management)\n- (PROSPECT inversion restricted to the 1700-2400 nm spectral domain (IO3):Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When using an appropriate spectral domain with no training data required)\n- (leaf optical datasets collected by different operators, devices and acquisition conditions:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When the machine learning workflow lacks oversight of data diversity across acquisition sources)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: machine learning regression models trained on non-representative public leaf datasets (LOPEX, ANGERS), leaf optical datasets collected by different operators, devices and acquisition conditions\n  RiskMechanism: misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions\n  Mitigation: PROSPECT inversion restricted to the 1700-2400 nm spectral domain (IO3)",
