   "source": {
    "title": "A flexible and efficient knowledge-guided machine learning data assimilation (KGML-DA) framework for agroecosystem prediction in the US Midwest",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113880",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113880",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Process-based models are widely used to predict the agroecosystem dynamics, but such modeled results often contain considerable uncertainty due to the imperfect model structure, biased model parameters, and inaccurate or inaccessible model inputs. Data assimilation (DA) techniques are widely adopted to reduce prediction uncertainty by calibrating model parameters or dynamically updating the model state variables using observations. However, high computational cost, difficulties in mitigating model structural error, and low flexibility in framework development hinder its applications in large-scale agroecosystem predictions. In this study, we addressed these challenges by proposing a novel DA framework that integrates a Knowledge-Guided Machine Learning (KGML)-based surrogate with tensorized ensemble Kalman filter (EnKF) and parallelized particle swarm optimization (PSO) to effectively assimilate historical and in-season multi-source remote sensing data. Specifically, we incorporate knowledge from a process-based model, ecosys, into a Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU)-based hierarchical neural network. The hierarchical architecture of KGML-DA mimics key processes of ecosys and builds a causal relationship between target variables. Using carbon budget quantification in the US Corn-Belt as a context, we evaluated KGML-DA's performance in predicting key processes of the carbon cycle at three agricultural sites (US-Ne1, US-Ne2, US-Ne3), along with county-level (627 counties) and 30-m pix"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops deep learning surrogate models for crop yield estimation across the Corn Belt, producing county-level and pixel-level yield predictions from remote sensing data such as SLOPE GPP compared against NASS yield records. The work touches on ethics at two principal junctures: the use of deep learning models for spatially resolved estimation, and the reliance on geographic data whose coverage may be uneven across rural and remote regions. The paper explicitly acknowledges spatial heterogeneity in its parameters and soil properties, and documents regions—for example the northwest and southwest Corn Belt, north Missouri, eastern North Dakota, and northern Nebraska—where prediction error and yield bias are elevated. These acknowledgements are the points at which the paper's technical contribution comes into contact with the category-level risks tracked in this audit.\n\nTurning to the causal risk reasoning, it is important to state at the outset that none of the four validated triples is instantiated by this paper; all four are disclosures of category-level risk rather than findings against the paper's own contribution. The reasoning chains are nonetheless well-defined and strongly grounded in the paper's text. Deep learning models for spatially resolved estimation belong to a class that can promote estimation bias under the condition that estimates are used to inform resource allocation amid spatial heterogeneity of parameters and soil properties, and the paper does document such heterogeneity and elevated error in specific regions. Similarly, geographic data scarcity in rural and remote areas is associated with estimation bias when datasets fail to represent the actual target regions—though notably the paper reports credible out-of-sample performance and, apart from two water-limited regions, no significant RMSE increase beyond its core states, which weakens rather than confirms the triggering of this risk here. Downstream, such estimation bias is associated in general with inequitable resource allocation from misclassification and with inequitable resource and service distribution, both framed as equal-rights concerns and both conditional on the models actually being used to facilitate resource allocation, land-use management, or disaster preparedness. Because this paper does not itself perform these downstream allocation actions, these impacts remain potential category associations. In short, the paper documents its own biases honestly—overestimation of yield for low-yield counties, regionally elevated error under an assumption of homogeneous crop parameters—but it does not instantiate the equity harms that would arise only if those outputs were operationalized for resource decisions.\n\nThe mitigating posture here is largely the paper's own transparency: it quantifies and localizes its prediction error, reports out-of-sample performance, and openly flags the homogeneous-parameter assumption as the source of regional bias, rather than concealing these limitations. No dedicated fairness or bias-correction mechanism is claimed within the provided triples. The overall auditor's judgement is that of the four risks tracked, zero are actually instantiated by this paper and all four are disclosures of risks inherent to the broader class of population/yield estimation methods. The causal chains behind these disclosures are strongly grounded in the paper's text and technically coherent, but because the paper stops at estimation and does not itself carry out downstream resource allocation, and because it partly neutralizes the data-scarcity concern through demonstrated out-of-sample robustness, no ethical harm can properly be attributed to this paper's contribution. The audit therefore records category-level disclosure only, with no instantiated finding against the work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (deep learning models for population mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When county-level and pixel-level yield estimates are used to inform resource allocation under spatial heterogeneity of parameters and soil properties)\n- (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable resource allocation from misclassification:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n- (geographic data scarcity in rural and remote areas:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When datasets fail to represent actual target regions)\n- (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable resource and service distribution:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When models are used to facilitate resource allocation and disaster preparedness)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: deep learning models for population mapping, geographic data scarcity in rural and remote areas\n  RiskMechanism: population estimation bias\n  EthicalImpact: inequitable resource allocation from misclassification, inequitable resource and service distribution",
