   "id": "087",
   "source": {
    "title": "Influence of data and methods on high-resolution imagery-based tree species recognition considering phenology: The case of temperate forests",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2025.114654",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2025.114654",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Seasonal phenological transformations alter tree appearances, notably by influencing the size and color of the foliage. It has long been anticipated that such phenology induced characteristics can help address the tree-species recognition problem, a fundamental challenge in forest science. Yet, studies on tree-species recognition using remote sensing and phenological characteristics have been rare, due to the very limited availability of high spatiotemporal resolution observations. Moreover, the interactions between the effectiveness of phenological characteristics, remote sensing data, and the analytical methodologies have not yet been sufficiently explored. The understanding of how to integrate multi-temporal observations and phenological characteristics in tree-species recognition has been lacking. This study aims to identify principles for optimizing species recognition by combining data, methods, and phenological dynamics. This involves understanding the impact factors of various methodologies, and how they interact with phenological characteristics and datasets at different times and/or frequencies. The study was carried out using multi-temporal high-resolution optical images of a temperate forest, which were collected in 2021 during leaf growth and senescence periods between May and October, i.e., three leaf growth (May–August) and three leaf senescence (September–October) periods. The test site comprised 14 different tree classes, including 11 species, 2 genera, and 1"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops deep learning models for tree species recognition using multi-temporal high-resolution optical imagery, with the specific study carried out on a temperate forest whose data were collected in 2021 across leaf growth and senescence periods between May and October. Two aspects of this technical design touch on ethics. First, the recognition models are trained on samples whose class sizes are highly uneven across the target species, and second, the models are tuned to the phenological timing characteristic of a single temperate-forest site. Both of these design choices are where the paper's method makes contact with the risk mechanisms identified in the audit.\n\nTurning to the causal reasoning, two findings are actually instantiated by this paper. With moderate confidence, the auditor finds that training deep learning models on imbalanced samples promotes population bias, a risk conditioned on class sample sizes being highly uneven across target species; the paper's own experimental results support this, noting that sample imbalance is a main limitation as the number of targeted species increases and that models tend to allocate small-sample species to larger-sample classes. Also with moderate confidence, the auditor finds that tuning the models to temperate-forest phenological timing promotes population bias under the condition that models trained and validated on a single temperate site are applied to other forest types, since the study's phenology–timing relationship is acknowledged to be specific to temperate forests. Both findings are stated as plausible but qualified given their moderate grounding. Separately, the audit records two potential disclosures rather than findings: population bias, as a category-level mechanism, is associated in general with resource allocation inequality in the context of land use and resource management, an equal-rights concern. These are reported strongly at the category level but are not triggered as harms by this paper's own contribution — the paper does not itself perform resource allocation, so this remains a disclosure of the risk class to which population-bias-prone methods belong, not an accusation against this work.\n\nIn terms of mitigations, the paper does address one adjacent risk that is therefore not triggered here: the auditor notes that denoising of pixel-based species maps without crown boundaries can, in general, cause over-smoothing that diminishes the representation of small-population species, but this paper does not instantiate that harm, and it is raised only to acknowledge the concern is recognized. The paper further points toward remediation of its instantiated bias risk by observing that the gaps among proportional sample sizes should be minimized to achieve unbiased results. Overall, the auditor's judgement is that two of the five triples represent risks actually instantiated by this paper — both concerning population bias arising from imbalanced samples and single-site temperate tuning — and both rest on moderate rather than strong grounding, so they are presented as qualified findings rather than definitive conclusions. The remaining risks are strong at the category level but are disclosures only, and one further risk is not triggered at all. No instantiated finding rises to a strong, unqualified level, and the downstream equal-rights impacts remain conditional and undischarged by this paper's scope.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (deep learning models for tree species recognition trained on imbalanced samples:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When class sample sizes are highly uneven across target species)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n- (denoising of pixel-based species maps without crown boundaries:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When crown boundaries are unknown and over-smoothing removes small-population species)\n- (deep learning models tuned to temperate-forest phenological timing:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: when models are trained/validated only on a single temperate site and applied to other forest types)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: deep learning models for tree species recognition trained on imbalanced samples, denoising of pixel-based species maps without crown boundaries, deep learning models tuned to temperate-forest phenological timing\n  RiskMechanism: population bias\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality",
