   "id": "088",
   "source": {
    "title": "Understanding the robustness of spectral-temporal metrics across the global Landsat archive from 1984 to 2019 – a quantitative evaluation",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113823",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113823",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "The Landsat archive is one of the richest Earth observation datasets available and provides long-term data at fairly high temporal and spatial resolution globally. Temporal aggregation is frequently used to condense single observations into a more digestible feature space that provides spatially gap-free data to fulfill demands of many processing strategies that rely on homogeneous data coverage across a large area, e.g., machine learning-based land cover classification. Spectral Temporal Metrics (STMs) represent a conceptually simple feature space wherein multiple observations are temporally aggregated by statistical functions. The quality and inter-annual consistency of STMs is affected by data availability, including usable clear-sky observations that vary in time and space due to satellite lifecycles, sensor failures, changes of observation modes, climate regimes, orbital overlaps, as well as inter-annual variability of cloud cover. However, the relationship between data availability and STM consistency between years is still poorly understood, especially as differences in STMs between years can both result from inter-annual variability in data availability, as well as inter-annual variability of land surfaces. In this study, we systematically quantify the effect of inter-annual data availability on annual STMs for the years 1984–2019, while completely controlling for inter-annual land surface changes. Our results are expected to help assess where on Earth, and in what pe"
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper undertakes a systematic assessment of spectral-temporal metrics (STMs) derived from Landsat imagery, quantifying how their quality and multi-annual consistency vary as a function of data availability and climate regime. The authors explicitly acknowledge that inter-annual variability in Landsat data availability—driven by satellite lifecycles, sensor failures, changing observation modes, orbital overlaps, and above all cloud cover—shapes the quality of the resulting metrics. This is where the work touches ethics: the paper establishes that STM reliability is spatially and temporally uneven, and that the degree of unevenness is climate-zone dependent. These findings constitute the concrete triggers of the audit, since the paper's own analysis surfaces both a data-availability effect and a regional-quality disparity.\n\nTurning to the causal reasoning, two instantiated findings emerge from the paper's own results. First, with moderate confidence, the auditor finds that inter-annual variability in Landsat data availability promotes unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks, but only conditionally—specifically when clear-sky observations are sparse or seasonally clustered in cloud-prone climates, degrading STM reliability. This is qualified rather than absolute: the paper documents that fully humid snow climates carry high but systematic (biased-yet-repeatable) errors, while equatorial and temperate climates exhibit unbiased but uncertain metrics whose accuracy or precision can exceed specification threefold. Second, again with moderate confidence, the climate-zone-dependent quality of the metrics promotes a regional disparity in monitoring reliability that disadvantages data-poor climates; the paper itself reports \"huge regional differences,\" with arid climates achieving the highest quality and consistency while tropical, equatorial and other data-poor regions inherently receive lower-quality metrics. This is a plausible equity concern grounded in the paper's stated results, though presented as a qualified inference rather than a firmly asserted conclusion. By contrast, the downstream chain from prediction unreliability to systemic failure in disaster or safety monitoring is, although strongly supported at the category level, only a POTENTIAL disclosure: this paper does not itself deploy STMs in a safety-critical monitoring pipeline. It belongs to a class of work whose unreliable metrics could, in principle, contribute to safety-monitoring failure, but the paper does not instantiate that harm—indeed, its stated aim is to \"help assess where on Earth, and in what periods, specific metrics can be used or should be avoided when multi-annual consistency is required,\" which is a cautionary rather than deploying posture.\n\nOn mitigation, the paper's central methodological contribution is itself protective: it strongly and explicitly inhibits the reliability risk by statistically quantifying the accuracy, precision, and uncertainty (APU) of STMs across Landsat spectral bands by comparing baseline and degraded time series. This uncertainty-quantification framework directly targets the unreliability mechanism in high-risk remote-sensing applications, giving downstream users the means to know where metrics fall inside or outside specification. Overall, the auditor judges that of the four validated triples, three are instantiated by this paper and one is a category-level disclosure only. The two instantiated risk findings—data-availability-driven unreliability and climate-zone-dependent regional disparity—are both held at moderate confidence and both conditional, so they should be read as qualified, well-scoped concerns rather than firm indictments. The single instantiated mitigation is strongly grounded and is in fact the paper's core contribution, materially offsetting the reliability risk it characterizes. The gravest chain, physical harm from safety-monitoring failure, is not triggered here and appears only as a disclosure. On balance, this is a diagnostic and mitigation-oriented paper: it surfaces genuine equity and reliability concerns in remote-sensing metrics while simultaneously providing the uncertainty tooling to manage them.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (inter-annual variability in Landsat data availability:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When clear-sky observations are sparse or seasonally clustered in cloud-prone climates, degrading STM reliability)\n- (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systemic failure in disaster or safety monitoring:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Earth observation imaging process)\n- (uncertainty quantification (APU framework):Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (climate-zone-dependent STM quality of Landsat metrics:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (regional disparity in monitoring reliability disadvantaging data-poor climates:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <inferred | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When tropical/equatorial and data-poor regions inherently receive lower-quality metrics than arid or infrastructure-rich regions)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: inter-annual variability in Landsat data availability, climate-zone-dependent STM quality of Landsat metrics\n  RiskMechanism: unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks\n  EthicalImpact: systemic failure in disaster or safety monitoring, regional disparity in monitoring reliability disadvantaging data-poor climates\n  Mitigation: uncertainty quantification (APU framework)",
