   "id": "092",
   "source": {
    "title": "Mapping recreational marine traffic from Sentinel-2 imagery using YOLO object detection models",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2025.114791",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2025.114791",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Identifying where maritime activities take place, and quantifying their potential impact on marine biodiversity, is important for the sustainable management of marine areas, spatial planning and marine conservation. Detection and monitoring of small vessels, such as pleasure crafts, has been challenging due to limited data availability with adequate temporal and spatial resolution. Here, we develop an analysis framework to detect and quantify small vessels, using openly available Sentinel-2 optical imagery, and the YOLO-family object detection models. We also show how existing spatial datasets can be used to improve the quality of the model output. We chose five distinct marine areas along the Finnish coast in the northern Baltic Sea and manually annotated 8,768 vessels for training and validating object detection models. The top-performing model, based on F1-score, achieved a test set F1-score of 0.863 and an mAP50 of 0.888. This model was then used to quantify pleasure crafts in the southern part of Finland from May to September 2022, using all available Sentinel-2 images with sufficient image quality. Detected recreational traffic was primarily concentrated on boating lanes and close to marinas, with weekend traffic averaging approximately twice the volume of weekday traffic. The developed approach can be used to identify areas with high boat traffic, thus supporting sustainable spatial planning, ecological impact avoidance, and serving as an indicator of recreational popu"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops an object-detection pipeline that identifies recreational vessels in openly available satellite imagery over the Finnish Baltic coast, evaluates detection performance with standard metrics, and geo-references the predicted bounding boxes back into the coordinate reference system of the original imagery. Several of these technical steps touch on ethics. The georeferencing of vessel detections and the potential public sharing of the resulting vessel-movement data are the points where the work intersects with privacy concerns, since georeferenced detections near marinas and enclosed bays can, in principle, expose patterns of individual behavior. Its aggregate performance evaluation and its training data—drawn exclusively from Finnish Baltic coastal tiles—are the points where the work intersects with fairness and bias concerns.\n\nTurning to the causal reasoning, the auditor separates what this paper actually instantiates from what its methods merely belong to as a category. Two findings are instantiated. First, the paper evaluates detection performance using non-spatially-explicit aggregate metrics (precision, recall, F1-score, mAP), reporting a single top-line result (F1 of 0.863, mAP50 of 0.888); under the condition that performance is measured only as a corpus-wide aggregate, this promotes an evaluation bias that can hide regional variability. This is a strong finding stated directly, and the paper's own results bear it out, with one scene scoring an F1 as low as 0.487. Second, because the training and evaluation corpora lack geographic diversity—being drawn only from Finnish Baltic coastal tiles while the approach is explicitly claimed to be \"scalable for estimating boat traffic across large areas, even globally\"—the work instantiates a spatial data bias. This too is a strong finding, grounded directly in the authors' own scalability claim. The remaining three triples are disclosures of category-level risk that this paper does not itself trigger. The public sharing of personal vehicle trajectory data and the georeferencing step belong to a class of techniques that can promote privacy violations, conditional on quantifying where and when individuals use marine areas or on exposing home locations, workspaces, and daily trajectories—but the paper does not perform that individual-level quantification, so this is noted only as a disclosure, not a finding against the paper. Likewise, the evaluation bias identified above belongs to a chain that can, when geoparsers are deployed downstream, promote reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions; this downstream fairness harm is a potential consequence rather than something this paper instantiates.\n\nThe paper presents no explicit mitigations within the provided triples, and none of the triples were tagged as neutralizing a risk. In the auditor's overall judgement, two of the five validated risks are actually instantiated by this paper's contribution—the aggregate-only evaluation masking regional variability and the geographically narrow training corpus underpinning a global scalability claim—and both are well-grounded, supported by strong confidence and by the paper's own reported results and claims. The other three risks, concerning privacy through trajectory sharing and georeferencing, and downstream fairness in underserved regions, are disclosures of category-level risk that this paper does not trigger and that in several cases hold only under stated conditions the paper does not meet. The instantiated findings are therefore both concrete and modest in number, while the privacy concerns should be read as cautionary context rather than as harms this particular work realizes.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (public sharing of personal vehicle trajectory data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When quantifying where and when individuals use marine areas, including recreational vessel movements)\n- (geo-referencing:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When exposing home locations, workspaces, and daily trajectories via georeferenced vessel detections near marinas and enclosed bays)\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of geoparsers for downstream geospatial tasks)\n- (lack of geographic diversity in training and evaluation corpora:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (spatial data bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When training data is drawn only from Finnish Baltic coastal tiles yet the approach is claimed scalable globally)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: public sharing of personal vehicle trajectory data, geo-referencing, non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score, lack of geographic diversity in training and evaluation corpora\n  RiskMechanism: evaluation bias hiding regional variability, spatial data bias\n  EthicalImpact: privacy violation, reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions",
