   "id": "094",
   "source": {
    "title": "Assessing the accuracy of Sentinel-2 instantaneous subpixel shorelines using synchronous UAV ground truth surveys",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2022.113293",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2022.113293",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2022",
    "abstract": "Due to recent technological advancements in the field of cloud-based satellite remote sensing, the barriers to global analysis ready dataset access and processing have lowered drastically increasing the opportunity for large-scale long-term satellite-derived shoreline monitoring solutions. However, validation studies employing synchronous and independent in-situ instantaneous shorelines at scale are limited. Thanks to a unique dataset of 47 synchronous UAV photogrammetric surveys in 15 coastal locations in Victoria, Australia, over 3 years, we validated Sentinel-2 instantaneous subpixel shorelines extracted using the most common water indices, CoastSat and a tidal-balanced convolutional neural network (Unet+++). We assessed the accuracy of the water level estimation using 9 wave run-up models and wave data sourced from a nearshore wave buoy network, a regional hindcast model and a global altimeter wave dataset. This paper also presents the first validation of Deep Learning-derived shorelines using synchronous independent in-situ data. We found the best overall performance and least threshold-sensitive shoreline extraction approach to be the WI index, whilst NDWI had the poorest performances despite being the most utilized across the literature. We found that the thresholdless Unet+++ solution coupled with an ensemble wave run-up model and the altimeter wave data is an adequate trade-off in terms of accuracy, adaptability and wave data access for global scale shoreline studies"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper develops a method for extracting satellite-derived shorelines (SDS) from Sentinel-2 imagery, training a tidal-balanced convolutional neural network to produce subpixel shorelines and validating its performance against groundtruth shorelines derived from UAV surveys. The groundtruth data itself is the product of an opportunistic, volunteered-geographic-information (VGI) collection effort: Digital Surface Models were built via Structure-from-Motion and Multiview Stereo algorithms from UAV imagery autonomously collected by citizen scientists along the Victorian coast, Australia, yielding 47 matches across 15 locations. Two aspects of this work touch ethics directly. First, the reliance on VGI and opportunistic data collection—dependent on who has access to technology and interest in volunteering data—is a genuine trigger. Second, the use of a black-box deep neural network for image segmentation, whose fixed probabilistic threshold operates over self-adjustable, hard-to-interpret pixel probabilities, is an instantiated design choice in this paper.\n\nTwo risks are actually instantiated by this paper's contribution, and both are strongly grounded. As a firm auditor finding, the opportunistic VGI collection promotes algorithmic bias, conditional on data collection depending on access to smartphones or willingness to volunteer data—a condition the paper's Victorian-coast citizen-science dataset meets. Also as a firm finding, the black-box nature of the trained CNN promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability; the paper's own text acknowledges the difficulty of attributing why performance varies and admits that no single method is consistently best along the coast. Beyond these instantiated findings, several risks appear only as category-level disclosures that this paper does not itself trigger. The algorithmic bias just noted belongs to a class that, in general, can promote unfair distribution of resources and services *if* biased and unvalidated analytics were used to drive city-wide planning—but this is conditional and not performed here; the paper instead cautions that accuracies from 15 Victorian sites may not transfer to other tidal and wave regimes. Likewise, the lack of transparency belongs to a class associated with safety risks in high-risk missions, and algorithmic focus bias with unfair resource distribution, but neither is instantiated by this study. Notably, one related risk—algorithmic focus bias from training on narrow geographies—is not triggered: the authors deliberately captured a broad range of beach types, widths, grainsizes, tidal ranges, and wave conditions across embayed and open-ocean environments, addressing rather than raising this concern.\n\nOn mitigations, the paper points toward a bias-reducing strategy: it proposes using an ensemble run-up model rather than a single best-performing one to encompass more morphodynamic environments and wave conditions globally, which inhibits algorithmic bias when combining multiple data sources—though this is offered conditionally and as a recommendation. Overall, the auditor's judgement is that of seven validated triples, only two are actually instantiated by this paper—both strongly grounded findings concerning VGI-driven bias and CNN opacity—while four are merely disclosures of category-level risk that this paper does not trigger, and one is a risk the paper actively neutralizes through its deliberately diverse training data. The two instantiated findings are well-grounded in the paper's own text and method, but they are largely disclosed and partially self-mitigated by the authors, who transparently flag the geographic limits of their accuracy claims and the unexplained variability of their black-box model.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (vgi and opportunistic data collection:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When data collection depends on access to technology like smartphones or interest in volunteering data.)\n- (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (unfair distribution of urban resources and services:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When biased analytics are used to determine city-wide planning and service distribution.)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (deep-learning algorithm for image segmentation beam:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic focus bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When training data is specific to informal dwellings but applied to formal or industrial city areas.)\n- (algorithmic focus bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (unfair distribution of urban resources and services:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When biased analytics are used to determine city-wide planning and service distribution.)\n- (data integration and modeling:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When used to correct bias in crowdsourced or VGI datasets by combining multiple data sources.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: vgi and opportunistic data collection, black-box nature of deep neural networks, deep-learning algorithm for image segmentation beam\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic bias, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, algorithmic focus bias\n  EthicalImpact: unfair distribution of urban resources and services, safety risks in critical missions\n  Mitigation: data integration and modeling",
