   "id": "096",
   "source": {
    "title": "Effectiveness of machine learning methods for water segmentation with ROI as the label: A case study of the Tuul River in Mongolia",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2021.102497",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2021.102497",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2021",
    "abstract": "The carrying capacity of water resources is key to the sustainable development of arid and semi-arid regions. There are important challenges related to the detection of discontinuous and crooked water bodies in the vast Mongolian Plateau, despite the availability of remote sensing technology which has the advantage of facilitating water observations over large areas and timelines. Given the high cost and low coverage of high-resolution images and the low resolution of images with high coverage, this study proposes a pixel-based convolutional neural network (CNN) method for the application of water extracted from the region of interest (ROI) to medium-resolution Landsat images. The pixel-based CNN method combines the texture and spectral features of the ground object by connecting the center pixels of the images to the surrounding pixels. ROI is used instead of full-label datasets, reduce the difficulty of building labels in low-to-medium-resolution images. Taking the Tuul River in Mongolia as a case, the pixel-based CNN method, the normalized difference water index threshold (NDWI) method, the modified normalized difference water index (MNDWI) threshold method, U-net model in deep learning, and the pixel-based deep neural network (DNN) method were used with medium-resolution Landsat 8 images with ROI labels. The pixel-based CNN method shows better water extraction results for the cloud, cloud shadows, and building areas, compared with other methods. The method proposed in thi"
   },
   "report": "**GeoAI Ethics Audit**\n\nThis paper addresses water body extraction from remote sensing imagery over Mongolia, employing a suite of deep learning classification methods—specifically the U-net semantic segmentation model, a pixel-based DNN, and a pixel-based CNN—to delineate water bodies. The stated purpose of this work is to supply hydrological data in support of sustainable water resource management, flood disaster risk reduction, and animal husbandry development. The ethically salient points of contact arise from two features: the paper's reliance on deep neural network architectures, and its dependence on training data drawn from a geographically specific target region whose land cover is described by the authors as relatively simple.\n\nThe single risk actually instantiated by this paper's contribution is the lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability that follows from the black-box nature of deep neural networks. Because the study directly employs U-net, DNN, and CNN models, this trigger is grounded in the paper's own method, and the auditor reports it as a well-supported (STRONG) finding: the models used here are inherently difficult to interpret and explain. The remaining risks are disclosures at the category level rather than findings against this paper. The concern that unrepresentative geographic training data can promote population bias belongs to a class of risk associated with this type of work, but the condition attaches only when datasets fail to represent actual target regions; the paper does not instantiate this, and the authors themselves flag—rather than exhibit—the limitation that Mongolia's simple land cover leaves the method's performance on complex surfaces unverified. Downstream, population bias could in turn promote resource allocation inequality in the context of land use and resource management (a conditional, moderate-confidence linkage), but since the upstream bias is not instantiated here, this too remains a disclosure. Likewise, while the lack of algorithmic transparency can, in high-risk remote sensing applications, promote safety risks in critical missions, this paper does not perform the triggering action; it merely notes the related limitation that optical imagery is hard to obtain in the bad weather accompanying floods. That physical-harm pathway is therefore reported only as a category-level, conditional disclosure, not as a finding against this work.\n\nThe paper offers no explicit mitigation for the transparency deficit it instantiates, though it does exercise transparency of a different kind by candidly acknowledging its own data and imaging limitations. In the auditor's overall judgement, of the four validated triples only one is actually instantiated by this paper—the black-box opacity of the deep learning models used—and that single finding is strongly grounded in the paper's own description of its methods. The other three are merely disclosed category-level risks, each hedged by a condition the paper does not meet, concerning geographic data bias, downstream resource inequality, and safety in critical missions. The paper is thus largely ethics-silent with respect to actively realized harms: its ethical exposure is confined to one well-grounded, but unmitigated, transparency concern, with all remaining risks appropriately treated as disclosures rather than findings.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When datasets fail to represent actual target regions)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: unrepresentative geographic training data, black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: population bias, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, safety risks in critical missions",
