   "source": {
    "title": "DPF-Net: Physical imaging model embedded data-driven underwater image enhancement",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2025.07.031",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2025.07.031",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Due to the complex interplay of light absorption and scattering in the underwater environment, underwater images experience significant degradation. This research presents a two-stage underwater image enhancement network called the Data-Driven and Physical Parameters Fusion Network (DPF-Net), which harnesses the robustness of physical imaging models alongside the generality and efficiency of data-driven methods. We train the Degraded Parameters Estimation Module (DPEM) on synthetic datasets with preset physical parameters as ground truth. This approach learns more authentic underwater imaging model, contrasting with prior works that directly fit raw-to-reference image mappings through the imaging equation. This module is subsequently trained in conjunction with an enhancement network, where the estimated physical parameters are integrated into a data-driven model within the embedding space. During model training, in addition to traditional reference-based losses, we use a degradation consistency loss to ensure physical consistency. Furthermore, we propose a new weak reference loss term that leverages the color distribution of the entire training set, thereby alleviating the reliance of our model on the quality of individual reference images. Our proposed DPF-Net demonstrates superior performance compared to other benchmark methods across multiple test sets, achieving state-of-the-art results. The source code and pre-trained models are available on the project home page: https"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThe paper under review develops an underwater image enhancement method intended to support downstream vision tasks, incorporating a physical enhancement model (DPEM) alongside a novel weakly supervised reference loss that constrains the model output toward the aggregate color distribution of its entire training corpus (the UIEB training set). This design decision is where the paper most directly touches ethics: by leveraging a single, corpus-wide color-distribution target rather than relying on individual reference images, the method's own architecture instantiates a specific evaluation-related mechanism. The paper also situates itself, in principle, within the space of enhancement for downstream safety-critical missions and acknowledges limitations of its physical assumptions under strongly directional artificial lighting and in extreme scenarios not well-represented in training.\n\nThe one finding this auditor identifies as actually instantiated by the paper's contribution stems from the weakly supervised reference loss. By using the whole training corpus as a single aggregate color-distribution target, the method can, under the stated condition, mask regional and water-type variability and thereby promote an evaluation bias that hides such variability. This finding is presented with moderate confidence: it is grounded in the paper's own description of the loss term, though the risk holds specifically under the condition that the aggregate distribution is used to hide regional heterogeneity, and should be read as plausible and qualified rather than definitive. The remaining risks are disclosures only and are not triggered by this paper. The connection from enhancement for safety-critical missions to prediction of incorrect results in high-risk geospatial applications is a potential, category-level risk conditioned on enhanced imagery being trusted in extreme, under-represented scenarios—something this paper does not itself perform; it flags, rather than instantiates, this concern. Likewise, the downstream chains from incorrect predictions to threats to human safety in emergency situations, and from evaluation bias to reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions, are strong in their general causal reasoning but remain potential for this paper: they describe risks belonging to the class of methods this work inhabits, conditioned respectively on deployment in disaster-response missions and across diverse water regions, without being instantiated by the paper's actual method.\n\nIn terms of mitigations, the paper's own framing offers partial self-limitation: it explicitly acknowledges that DPEM's physical parameters may be inaccurate under non-uniform attenuation, and it identifies extreme low-light imagery (183 images) as falling outside its training distribution, which tempers overclaims about applicability in the very scenarios where the downstream harms would materialize. Overall, this auditor's judgement is that of the four validated triples, only one is actually instantiated by the paper—the evaluation-bias mechanism arising from the aggregate color-distribution loss—and it is moderately, not strongly, grounded. The remaining three are disclosures of category-level risk that this paper does not trigger, including the more serious safety and fairness impacts, which are downstream of actions the paper does not take. The contribution therefore raises no fully instantiated harm to human safety or regional fairness; its single genuine finding is a qualified concern about how corpus-wide evaluation may obscure regional variability, and the paper's stated limitations reflect at least some awareness of the boundaries of its method.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (underwater image enhancement for downstream vision tasks in safety-critical missions:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When enhanced imagery is trusted in extreme scenarios not well-represented in training)\n- (prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (threats to human safety in emergency situations:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When applied to safety-critical missions like disaster response)\n- (weakly supervised reference loss constraining output to UIEB training-set color distribution:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When the entire training corpus is used as a single aggregate color-distribution target hiding regional/water-type variability)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of models for downstream geospatial tasks across diverse water regions)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: underwater image enhancement for downstream vision tasks in safety-critical missions, weakly supervised reference loss constraining output to UIEB training-set color distribution\n  RiskMechanism: prediction of incorrect results in high-risk grs applications, evaluation bias hiding regional variability\n  EthicalImpact: threats to human safety in emergency situations, reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions",
