   "source": {
    "title": "Monthly monitoring of urban development and renewal at the block-level in China using Sentinel-2 time series",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2025.115070",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2025.115070",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Urban renewal has been elevated to a national strategy in China, leading to rapid development and transformation of street blocks. However, monitoring construction events at high temporal resolution remains challenging due to the limitations of existing methods, which often struggle with noise interference and lack continuous monitoring capabilities. To address this, we propose Semantic Similarity Contrast-based Street Block Monitoring (SSC-SB), a method that leverages Sentinel-2 time series imagery for automated, high-frequency detection of street block development and renewal. By extracting deep semantic features with a pretrained encoder, SSC-SB analyzes similarity curves to identify development and demolition construction events. Applied to the Middle Yangtze River Basin (MYRB) urban agglomeration shows that SSC-SB achieves 90.4% spatial domain accuracy, with construction start and end date detection accuracies of 68.8% and 54.9%, respectively. Results indicate an increasing emphasis on urban renewal, as demolished street blocks outnumbered new developments for the first time in 2023, with Hunan Province leading in renewal efforts, where renewal blocks accounted for 41.5% of all changed street blocks, reflecting a balanced focus on expansion and infrastructure renewal. Transfer experiments in Xi’an further demonstrate that SSC-SB retains up to 80% of the performance of a locally trained model when applied across regions without fine-tuning, indicating a decent level of ge"
   },
   "report": "**Ethics Audit**\n\nThe paper introduces SSC-SB, a method that extracts deep semantic features using a pretrained encoder and analyzes similarity curves to identify development and demolition construction events across urban street blocks. Its stated purpose is to help governments assess urban renewal progress from a macro perspective, aggregating construction and renewal statistics at the provincial and city level. The method touches ethics at two primary points that this paper actually exercises: first, its demolition detection capability, which flags street blocks undergoing renewal; and second, its reliance on single-region training data (the MYRB dataset) that is subsequently applied across domains, including transfer experiments to other cities without fine-tuning.\n\nTurning to the causal risk reasoning, two findings are actually instantiated by this paper's method, both at moderate confidence. The first is that SSC-SB's demolition detection, by identifying blocks undergoing renewal, can plausibly promote harm to displaced or vulnerable populations — but this holds only under the stated condition that the detection signals renewal without capturing displacement outcomes or community input. As a moderate-confidence finding, this is a plausible but qualified concern rather than a demonstrated harm: the paper does perform the triggering detection, yet the harm depends on how downstream actors use the signal. The second instantiated finding is that the paper's use of single-city training data applied cross-domain introduces population bias when the datasets fail to represent actual target regions; the paper itself acknowledges reduced cross-region performance, which grounds this concern, though again at moderate confidence. Separately, three risks are disclosures only and are not triggered by this paper's own contribution. The paper belongs to a class of methods where biased provincial or city-level renewal statistics could produce algorithmic focus bias, and where that bias — or the population bias noted above — could in turn drive an unfair distribution of urban resources and services or resource allocation inequality. While the causal step from bias to unequal resource distribution is strongly supported in general, these outcomes are conditional on the analytics being used to determine city-wide planning and service distribution, an action this paper does not itself perform. They should therefore be read as category-level disclosures, not as findings against this paper.\n\nThe auditor notes no explicit mitigations articulated in the provided evidence, aside from the paper's own transparency about degraded cross-region generalization, which at least surfaces the population-bias concern rather than concealing it. Overall, of the five validated triples, only two are actually instantiated by this paper's method, and both carry moderate rather than strong confidence — meaning the instantiated findings are plausible and grounded in the paper's stated capabilities but are qualified and conditional, not definitive harms. The remaining three, including the strongly supported causal links to equal-rights and resource-allocation impacts, are potential category risks that this paper does not trigger. The auditor's judgement is therefore that this paper carries a limited, conditional ethical footprint: its real exposure lies in demolition detection without displacement safeguards and in cross-domain population bias, while the broader distributional harms remain hypothetical absent the planning-and-service-allocation use the paper does not undertake.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (SSC-SB demolition detection identifying street blocks undergoing renewal:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (harm to displaced/vulnerable populations:EthicalImpact) [PsychologicalHarm]  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When demolition detection signals renewal without capturing displacement outcomes or community input)\n- (biased provincial/city-level renewal statistics from SSC-SB:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic focus bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When biased analytics are used to determine city-wide planning and service distribution.)\n- (algorithmic focus bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (unfair distribution of urban resources and services:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When biased analytics are used to determine city-wide planning and service distribution.)\n- (single-region training data (MYRB) applied cross-domain without fine-tuning:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When datasets fail to represent actual target regions)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: SSC-SB demolition detection identifying street blocks undergoing renewal, biased provincial/city-level renewal statistics from SSC-SB, single-region training data (MYRB) applied cross-domain without fine-tuning\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic focus bias, population bias\n  EthicalImpact: harm to displaced/vulnerable populations, unfair distribution of urban resources and services, resource allocation inequality",
